<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Implement Poverty Alleviation Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand said today that his government will implement
programs for families living below the poverty line and the
unemployed in the country in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass meeting organized by his National Democratic
Party (RPP) in East Nepal's Jhapa District, about 200 kilometers
from here, Chand pledged that details of these programs will be
made public.
</P>
<P>
He said the commitment to poverty alleviation and resolving the
unemployment problem is the main thrust of his coalition
government's policy.
</P>
<P>
Talking about his three-party government which was formed last
month to replace the former one led by the Nepali Congress (NC)
party, Chand said it will do something for the good of the country
and people.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali prime minister was touring the country over the
weekend as part of his party's campaign for the upcoming local
elections.
</P>
<P>
Chand's RPP party is the third largest in the country, but it
currently controls few of the country's more than 4,000 local
administration bodies at village, municipality and district
levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
