<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: PATA Travel Fair in China Successful (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The annual Travel Mart of the
Pacific Asia Travel Association (PATA), which was successfully
convened in Beijing from April 17-19, marks a milestone in the
fair's 20-year history.
</P>
<P>
The event drew a record-breaking 1,650 buyers and sellers from
about 60 countries and regions the world over.
</P>
<P>
"The strength of this year's mart comes from the broad-based
support from throughout the region, and shows the growing interest
in Pacific Asia travel products and the industry's interest in
China as a destination," said Milton Cooke, PATA Director of
Marketing.
</P>
<P>
He praised the China Host Committee for its work in
incorporating the PATA event into the "Visit China 97" activities.
</P>
<P>
The first-time appearance at the mart of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK DPRK) was a highlight of the
two-and-a-half-day show.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good opportunity for our country to promote its tourist
products to China and to other countries," said Kim Hyok, a senior
manager of Korea International Travel Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
According to Kim, DPRK opened to overseas tourists on a large
scale in 1987. Last year, overseas tourist arrivals to DPRK topped
100,000, of which Chinese mainlanders accounted for 70 percent,
with the rest coming from Japan, Taiwan, southeast Asian and
European countries.
</P>
<P>
During the fair, representatives at DPRK's two booths held
business talks with about 80 travel businesses from China,
Australia, and European countries.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the Mart will help boost the tourism industry of our
country," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
While the strong presence of major players of the tourism and
travel industry of southeast Asian countries, such as Singapore,
Thailand, Malaysia, and Indonesia was evident, the dozen booths
set up by Vietnam -- a new member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Countries -- also attracted huge crowds.
</P>
<P>
According to Pham Phuoc Long, President of the Vietnam Chapter
of PATA, Vietnam sent its largest-ever delegation to this year's
show. While most of the participants were State-run travel
agencies, airlines, and hotels, the travel business which he
manages was the only private Vietnamese firm present.
</P>
<P>
"It is the economic opening-up policy that has pushed up the
tourism development of our country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam received one million overseas tourists in 1996 and this
year's target is set at 1.6 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese tourism officials think China was fortunate to
host this year's mart, since from 1998 on, the venue of PATA Mart
will be permanently located at the Suntec Exhibition Center in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Many PATA officials attributed the success of this year's fair
largely to China's charm as the world's fifth largest tourist
destination.
</P>
<P>
Leading Chinese travel agencies, major airlines, and upscale
hotels hosted 54 booths, the largest number among participating
countries.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that on the first day, 638 foreign buyers went
to 41 Chinese booths to talk business, with 114 letters of intent
signed.
</P>
<P>
"The Mart will contribute remarkably to the growth of China's
international tourism in 1998," said Zhao Ming, a sales manager of
the Head Office of China International Travel Agency, the
country's largest.
</P>
<P>
A number of tourist routes jointly promoted by Hong Kong, Macao
and the Chinese mainland also attracted attention.
</P>
<P>
Also present were Taiwan's travel agencies, airlines and
hotels. Tourist authorities from both sides of the Taiwan Straits
said they hope to see exchanges between tourist and travel
personnel of the two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
