<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Wall Street at Crossroads (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Investors at Wall Street is now
at the crossroads, wondering whether to buy, sell or hold.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, the Dow Jones industrial average recouped
312 points, having erased nearly half of its recent 700-point
slide. Asian and European markets generally followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Last week's relatively low volume and the limited blue-chip
focus of the market's advance prompted many analysts to question
the rebound's resiliency.
</P>
<P>
Arnold Kaufman, editor of Standard &AMP; Poor's weekly newsletter
The Outlook, said, "There's still a feeling that this is a minor
pullback, that people should buy on the dips."
</P>
<P>
When the blue chip gauge slid to 6,391.69 points on April 11,
some cooler heads warned against panic selling, saying that a
correction of 10 percent is a healthy sign after the extraordinary
gains of recent months. Since 1994, the stock market kept on going
up and hasn't had a major correction. The Dow touched 7,085.16,
the highest ever, on March 11.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has practically removed one of the main
supports for the bull market. Last month, the central bank raised
one of its key lending rates for the first time in two years as a
bid to slow the economy and prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
Stocks have fallen sharply over the past month amid worries
that profits will suffer if the Federal Reserve raises interest
rates again to reduce inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
It is even more difficult now to discuss bulls or bears after
the market has recovered a big proportion of lost territories.
</P>
<P>
In any case, the triple-digit losses on the Dow are less
dramatic than they look. With the Dow near 7,000, a fall of 150
points represents only 2 percent of the market's value. To match
the percentage loss of the October 1987 crash, the Dow would have
to lose about 1,420 points in one day.
</P>
<P>
As a trend of the past two weeks, strong earnings reports by
major technology issues like Intel and Microsoft did little to
bolster the sector.
</P>
<P>
While many are predicting that the market will either climb or
plunge, there's another saying: Maybe the market will simply
remain somewhere between bull and bear, or barely rising -- for a
long, long time.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the risk of devastating losses, some experts are
giving advice as to shifting some funds to the treasury or foreign
exchange market where yielding is getting higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
