<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bartoli Wins Liege-Bastogne-Liege Cycling Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian rider Michele Bartoli
won the 262km Liege-Bastogne-Liege classic cycling race on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
France's world number one Laurent Jalabert, of the ONCE team,
came second with Italy's Gabriele Colombo third.
</P>
<P>
Bartoli, who got away from Jalabert in the final kilometer in
the race, the fourth round of the World Cup, thus claimed his
second classic event after the Tour of Flanders last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Wall Street at Crossroads (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Generally speaking, the stock market has been growing in an
ideal economic environment, in which inflation and interest rates
have been kept low, the economy is growing, and corporate profits
are on the rise. But some analysts said that when things can't get
any better, they can only get worse, and that is something also
worried by many investors.
</P>
<P>
Most of the attention and worries are now focused on the
Federal Reserve. Chairman Alan Greenspan said several times that
the current stock prices are too high, and, with the Fed also
still worried about inflation, there is a real fear that last
month's interest-rate increase could lead to one or more.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the market is hanging more on high technology now.
When banks and financial-services companies do poorly when rates
are rising, investors turn their eyes more to technology shares.
The ups and downs of bellwether technology stocks, whose value
almost doubled over the past year, insert greater influence to the
market.
</P>
<P>
The hidden factors affecting growth of the market also include
the performance of major companies whose returns are so affected
by interest rates and support of investors.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that personal savings in the U.S. have fallen
from 9 percent in 1975 to about 5 percent today. Much of the money
now going into the stock market is money that used to go into
banks. But the flow has slowed down over the past month. The money
flown into the stock market through mutual funds decreased to 9.5
billion U.S. dollars in March from 18.5 billion U.S. dollars in
February.
</P>
<P>
According to some market observers, the market will have
trouble when the influx of funds was getting much slower. The New
York stock market's double-digit increase over the past two years
was also helped by the fast increase of investment.
</P>
<P>
It will probably be an all-time truth that investors who have
realistic goals and follow sound, long-term strategies can still
do well in a turbulent stock market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen-age Smokers in US Rise Sharply Over Last 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Teen-age Smokers in the United
States climbed sharply over the last five years, triggering off a
hot debate in the country of what has caused the teen-age smoking
rate rising so quickly.
</P>
<P>
Teen-age smoking rates declined in the 1970s and leveled off in
the 1980s. But last year, the percentage of 12th graders who
smoked daily was up 20 percent from 1991, to 22 percent, and the
rate among 10th graders jumped 45 percent, to 18.3 percent, and
the rate for 8th graders was up 44 percent, to 10.4 percent,
according to the most recent edition of the University of
Michigan's Monitoring the Future Survey, an annual study widely
followed by tobacco researchers.
</P>
<P>
Five people now younger than 18 will eventually die of
tobacco-related illnesses, at current smoking rates, according to
the most recent projections from the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta City.
</P>
<P>
Rising youth smoking rates have been cited by the Food and Drug
Administration and President Bill Clinton as evidence that the
tobacco industry is marketing its products in youths.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times said in a report today that the surge in
teen-age smoking in the 1990s coincided with a sharp expansion by
both Reynolds and Philip Moris, two big tobacco companies in the
United States, in giveaways of items like T-shirt in return for
coupons accumulated by buying their cigarettes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
