<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFP Leader Blames ANC for Crime, Social Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Inkatha
Freedom Party leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi today blamed the
African National Congress for its social problems when calling on
his party members to prepare for the 1999 national elections.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass rally at Lindelant, Kwazulu Natal Province,
Buthelezi said the IFP is needed in government to solve the
"bread-and-butter" problems of the people.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that escalating crime, unemployment and the
failure to create jobs was due to weaknesses in the African
National Congress-led government.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, also minister of home affairs in the cabinet,
criticized the ANC for monopolizing all aspects of policy
formation, noting that more autonomous provincial rule would
allow the IFP-controlled provincial legislature to deal with
social problems effectively.
</P>
<P>
He called on all the IFP communities, their leaders and
supporters to be more proactive in election campaigning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
