<HEADLINE> Gujral Writethru: Indian President Appoints New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Shanker Dayal
Sharma tonight appointed United Front (UF) leader I. K. Gujral the
country's 12th prime minister, bringing to an end three weeks of
political turmoil triggered by the Congress Party's withdrawal of
support to the government led by H. D. Deve Gowda on March 30.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Gujral, who will head a 16-party coalition,
came within less than 12 hours of his unanimous election as leader
of the UF parliamentary party earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The requisite oath of office and secrecy is scheduled to take
place at 10:00 hours tomorrow morning, an hour before the
parliament meets for a special session to pass the budget for
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The president directed Gujral to seek a vote of confidence in
the Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament) by Tuesday (April
22).
</P>
<P>
The 78-year-old Janata Dal (a major constituent of the United
Front) veteran, who was asked by the president to give the names
of those to be included in the Council of Ministers, told
reporters at the Presidential Palace here that he will finalize
the list tonight.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the United Front went to the president this morning
formally staking the front's claim to form a new government
shortly after electing Gujral as its parliamentary party leader.
</P>
<P>
The president decided to invite Gujral to form the government
after intensive discussions during the day with Senior leaders of
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), Atal Behari Vajpayee and L. K.
Advani, and Congress Party President Sitaram Kesri.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the Presidential Palace tonight said the
decision to invite Gujral to form a new government was taken in
view of the Congress Party pledging support to the new United
Front government and the BJP's indication of not being in a
position to form the government.
</P>
<P>
It said the decision was also taken on balance of
considerations relevant to national interest particularly the need
to avert a mid-term poll so soon after the general elections held
in 1996, less than a year ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
