<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EgyptAir to Ferry Back Libyan Pilgrims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- EgyptAir, the Egyptian national
flag carrier, will start ferrying back Libyan pilgrims from Saudi
Arabia from Saturday, an EgyptAir official said today.
</P>
<P>
The return flights will continue until May 8, Regional
Director of the airliner Nagdi Faraag told the Egyptian news
agency MENA.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir has done its best to make the annual Hajj season a
success for the Libyan pilgrims because of the special
relationship between the two brotherly countries and between
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Libyan leader Muammar
Gaddafi, he said.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir operated about 90 flights to carry 10,750 Libyans
from the Libyan cities of Benghazi and Tripoli to Mecca, the
Islamic holiest site, this year.
</P>
<P>
It has been allowed by the U.N. Security Council Committee on
Libya to provide the transport in the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
The move comes to relieve the difficulties that Libyan pilgrims
face in traveling on land or by sea, because of the U.N.
sanctions that limit diplomatic contacts, ban arms sales and
prohibit air traffic in and out of the African country.
</P>
<P>
However, Libya broke the embargo for the third consecutive
year on April 4 by flying 105 pilgrims, including members of an
official Libyan delegation, to Saudi Arabia on a Libyan Arab
Airways flight.
</P>
<P>
The plane returned to Libya the next morning.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has imposed an international embargo on Libya since
April 1992 for its refusal to hand over two Libyans suspected of
involvement in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet in Lockbie,
Scotland, which killed 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
