<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Calls for Votes in British Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army (IRA), held an annual party conference
today with a call for votes in Britain's May 1 election to force
the incoming government to lift a ban on its entry to Northern
Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, told some 500 delegates
that Sinn Fein votes in the election would put pressure on the
British government and pro-British unionist parties to end the ban
and talk.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, which shares the IRA goal of an end to British rule
and the reunification of Ireland, is confident of winning two to
three seats, which would present the next British government with
the dilemma of refusing to talk to elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Ireland and the United States have banned all contact
with Sinn Fein since the IRA ended a 17-month cease-fire in its
war against British rule in Northern Ireland in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Observers here suggest the IRA may call a truce after the
British election in a bid to get Sinn Fein to the peace talks
which are due to resume on June 3.
</P>
<P>
The Sinn Fein conference, in the Irish border town of Monaghan,
took place one day after the IRA claimed responsibility for bomb
blasts and warnings that created transport havoc on the British
mainland last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
