<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stadd: Israeli Prosecutor Drop Indictment Against Netanyahu (By Zhi Linfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Attorney-General
Elyakim Rubinstein announced today that no indictment would be
filed against Netanyahu for his involvement in the Bar-On
scandal, citing lack of sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced at a news conference here
attended by State Attorney Edana Arbel and other police and
justice officials. Repeatedly describing the alleged "Bar-On for
Hebron" scandal as a very difficult and complicated matter,
Rubinstein said the state prosecution decided to reject the
police recommendation to indict Netanyahu as well as Justice
Minister Tzahi Hanegbi because they thought there were no
court-tight evidence to file the indictments.
</P>
<P>
But Rubinstein said Shas party leader Aryeh Deri would be
charged with extortion in pushing for the appointment of
former Jerusalem Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general in order
to serve his private interests.
</P>
<P>
According to the exposure of Bar-On affair by the state
television Channel I, Deri reportedly conditioned Shas' support on
the Bar-On's appointment in hope to obtain a plea bargain
deal in pushing for Bar-On's appointment.
</P>
<P>
No decision was made on the police recommendation of
indictment against the Prime Minister's Office Director-General
Avigdor Liberman.
</P>
<P>
The tone of Rubinstein's statements was relatively soft on
Netanyahu, who he said that indeed suggested Bar-On's
appointment in order to appease his coalition ally Deri. But
the attorney-general pointed out that no solid evidence had
been obtained to prove that Deri's threats had reached
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"After closing the deliberation, we drew the conclusion that
we do not have sufficient and physical evidence with
sufficient grounds for proving that indeed there is criminal
offense on the part of the prime minister," Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
However, detailed report on the state Attorney's Office
reviewing of the police recommendations and materials will be
released late by State Attorney Arbel in a 80-page report.
The language used in her report is regarded as crucial to
Netanyahu who is striving to avert the collapse of the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Despite the escape from an indictment, Netanyahu still faces
a crisis of survival as some ministers might consider leaving
the government, whose image and credibility have been seriously
damaged by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that the likely defectors within the
cabinet included Likud's Finance Minister Dan Meridor and
Communications Minister Limor Livnat, Yisrael Baaliya's Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky and Absorption Minister Yuli Edelstein,
and The Third Way's Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
They have indicated their willingness to leave the government
if the state attorney's report contained scathing criticism of
Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's White Collar Staff Getting Sicker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain's white collar workers are
getting sicker, according to an absenteeism survey by the
Confederation of British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
The finding that sick leave among professionals has soared by
25 percent in the past two years is expected to be one of the main
conclusions of the biennial survey.
</P>
<P>
Manual workers are in better health than their professional
counterparts with the number of days off sick unchanged since the
last survey in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Management experts argue that Britain's industry is only now
taking the 12 billion pound (19.2 billion US dollar) annual cost
of sick days seriously by checking up on absent workers.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the CBI said, "Figures for 1996 show that 187
million working days were lost due to absence which averages 8.4
days per employee and cost employers around 530 pounds (848 US
dollars) per employee."
</P>
<P>
"While the absence rate for manual workers is largely unchanged
since 1994, there was a 25 percent increase in the rate for
skilled and professional staff," he added.
</P>
<P>
The figures also reveal that workers in the public sector are
33 percent more likely to be "off" than those in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The survey found employers that introduced family-friendly
policies were usually able to cut absence rates.
</P>
<P>
Companies were reported to be attempting to cut the number of
"sick" days taken by staff by mounting raids on those allegedly
ill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
