<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Female Graduates Remarkably Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The gender imbalances that
existed among graduates 10 years ago have virtually been
eradicated in South Africa, according to a latest survey by the
Human Sciences Research Council.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, only 39 percent of those who graduated from South
African universities were women, whereas in 1994 women
constituted almost half of the graduates, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 35 percent of all graduates in South
Africa held a postgraduate qualification in 1994, the survey
said.
</P>
<P>
On occupational income of graduates in the country, the survey
showed that the average income package of self-employed people
was 142,600 Rands (about 32,500 U.S. Dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, employees in the public sector earned 90,300
Rands (about 20,500 U.S. Dollars) and employees in the private
sector 117,100 Rands (nearly 26,600 U.S. Dollars). The top
earners were self-employed brokers, the survey added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
