<HEADLINE> Egypt Gets Message From Arafat Amid Intensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa received a message from Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat today amid intensified Egyptian diplomatic drive to
break the Mideast impasse.
</P>
<P>
Arafat gave a full assessment of the current situation in the
Middle East in the message handed over by Arafat's adviser
Marawan Kanafani, said Nabil Fahmi, political adviser to the
Egyptian foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Fahmi said that the coming stage will witness intensified
Egyptian and Palestinian coordination at all levels.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will also continue its contacts with all quarters
involved in the peace process, with the U.S. and EU in the lead,
in order to surmount the current crisis that stalks the peace
process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa has carried out intensive contacts and consultations
with senior officials at the Palestinian National Authority over
the past three days, according to Egyptian Gazette today.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Moussa also joined a meeting between Arafat and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy in Malta, in the first direct
official meeting between the Palestinian and Israeli sides since
the peace process plunged to the worst crisis in its seven-year
history since Israel decided to build a Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem last month.
</P>
<P>
In another move to step up its diplomatic campaign to restart
the peace talks, Egypt sent a top envoy to Washington last Tuesday
to present its ideas to push forward Arab-Israeli negotiations
when separate initiatives from the U.S. and the EU had flopped.
</P>
<P>
"We are awaiting the American initiative that U.S. President
Bill Clinton has referred to," Arafat's adviser Nabil Abu Redina
said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reasserted the Palestinian determination to keep
East Jerusalem intact before the final talks and to stop any
unilateral decision concerning the holy city.
</P>
<P>
"East Jerusalem is the red line that could not be trespassed, a
fact already recorded in the American letter of guarantees at
Madrid and the Oslo agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Contradicting to the Israeli claim, however, he pointed out
that security coordination with Israel has not been resumed after
two rounds of talks in Gaza since last Thursday that grouped
Arafat and senior U.S. and Israeli security officials.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu had demanded
Palestinians to halt violence but refused to halt the construction
of the Har Homa neighborhood, a move that has stranded the peace
talks and sparked almost daily clashes in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
