<HEADLINE> 2ndadd: Netanyahu Slams Opponents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- following the prosecution's
decision not to indict him over the Bar-On scandal, Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu slammed his opponents for launching a
de-legitimizing campaign against him and vowed to continue his
policies.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the nation on the private television Channel 2,
Netanyahu described himself as a victim of the witch-hunt
campaign launched by his political opponents who refused to
accept the results of last year's elections that swept him to
power.
</P>
<P>
"These attacks against me stem from one central motive, namely
the attempt to cause the government to fall because of
fundamental disagreements at all levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
He specifically attacked his political opponents for launching
the campaign to topple him just because he favored building the
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem, being committed to
maintaining the unity of Jerusalem, rejecting establishment of a
Palestinian state and refusing to return the Golan Heights to
Syria.
</P>
<P>
"They will not succeed ... we will continue to speaking on
your behalf: you, the voters who voted for me," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he might have made a mistake in the Bar-On
affair, but committed definitely no criminal offense. He said he
would draw a lession from the scandal and do everything possible
to correct the damage that had been done to his government.
</P>
<P>
He also blasted the media, especially state television Channel
I which broke the news on Bar-On affair in January, for personal
attacks against him. By deliberately choosing to speak on the
private Channel 2, Netanyahu was apparently venting his anger
toward Channel I.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was ready to accept the challenge ahead,
calling for the public trust and support to him in order to build
a better future.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this evening, Israeli Attorney-General Elyakim
Rubinstein announced not to indict Netanyahu as well as Justice
Minister Tzahi Hanegbi for their alleged involvement in the
"Bar-On for Hebron scandal" for lack of solid evidence in the
police recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Only Shas leader Aryeh Deri would be charged with extortion in
pushing for the appointment of former Jerusalem lawyer Roni
Bar-On as the attorney-general in January in hope to obtain a
plea bargain deal in his bribery trial. 
</P>
