<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Exports Continue to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean exports last year rose
by 24 percent in U.S. Dollar terms to exceed 2.49 billion U.S.
Dollars, while imports totaled 2.2 billion U.S. Dollars, Barclays
Bank Zimbabwe Ltd said here today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its economic review that the performance of
the exporting sector had helped improve Zimbabwe's gross foreign
reserves, which at the end of 1996 were estimated at 720 million
U.S. Dollars, or four months import cover.
</P>
<P>
The foreign reserves have, however, recently been under
pressure from importers ahead of new high tariffs which came into
effect last month, and import cover has since fallen to about
three months.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts expect the import cover to increase from
this month because of the large inflow of proceeds from this
year's tobacco auctions, which open on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the exporting sector has posted remarkable
gains in the past three years, with the cumulative increase in
exports in U.S. Dollars rising to 55 percent by the end of 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
