<HEADLINE> More SLA Militiamen Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) were killed and at least two others
wounded in two consecutive military operations today in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent retaliation for the death of its collaborators,
Israel sent warplanes to strike a suspicious guerrilla target on
the edge of the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone."
</P>
<P>
Police sources reported that Israeli warplanes launched an air
raid at vicinities of Sujoud, Jezzin, at 4:30 p.m. (13:30 GMT)
and fired two air-to-surface missiles. No casualties were caused
in the air strike.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Israeli-backed SLA Militia, led by retired
Lebanese army General Antoine Lahd, said that a SLA officer
identified as Asad Namour was Killed in a bomb blast in Bakasin,
Jezzin, this morning.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese guerrillas detonated a second bomb when a group of
militiamen led by Rimon Abu Marad, SLA's commander of the
Jezzin area, arrived at the scene to check the incident, killing
one militiaman and wounding at least two others.
</P>
<P>
Voice of the South, radio of the SLA armed by Israel to
patrol the buffer zone, confirmed that one of SLA officer was
killed in the town of Bakasin by a bomb planted apparently by
guerrillas in his car.
</P>
<P>
It added that in another attack, the guerrillas detonated a
bomb near the town when a SLA patrol comprising two vehicles was
passing by.
</P>
<P>
One vehicle was destroyed in the explosion, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israeli guerrillas, especially fighters of the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God. escalated their campaign
against the 2,500-strong SLA militia this month and refrained
from directly attacking the 1,000 Israeli occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
Today's operations raised the casualties of the SLA since this
year to five killed and 19 injured.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in south Lebanon also reported that early in
the afternoon, the guerrillas carried out attacks at Israeli
positions at Bir Kalab, Sujoud and Kassarah Aroush with
machine-guns and rocket-propelled grenades.
</P>
<P>
But no word on casualties was available.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli artillery bombarded Iglim Al-Toffah, or
Province of Apple, a mountain area some 60 kilometers southeast
of the capital of Beirut and often used by Lebanese guerrillas as
a springboard to attack the border enclave.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces bombarded Iglim Al-Toffah and West Beqaa on
Saturday night and early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes carried out reconnaissance flights over
Western Beqaa this morning, drawing upward ground fire opened by
the Lebanese Army's anti-air units in the area.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes also flew over the south Lebanese port city
of Tyre and nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 to curb cross-border attacks on northern Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
