<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Reduce Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean president Robert
Mugabe today said his government is committed to bringing down
the budget deficit which analysts said is one of the major
problem frustrating rapid economic growth of the country.
</P>
<P>
In his annual message to exhibitors at this year's 38th trade
fair, which starts on April 22 in Bulawayo, the country's second
largest city, the president noted the budget deficit was one of
the causes of macro-economic instability Zimbabwe has been
experiencing ever since market reforms were launched in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is in the year to June 1997 expected to
exceed 11 percent of gdp, compared with a target of about 8.5
percent, and this was mainly due to unbudgeted expenditure on
civil servants salary and bonus payments.
</P>
<P>
The president said measures being taken included rationalising
spending by commercialising parastatals, and in some cases
privatising them.
</P>
<P>
He added, "we are also improving efficiency and effectiveness
in the delivery of public services, while at the same time
enhancing our revenue collection systems without necessarily
raising taxes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
