<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Meets With Carter on Peace in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Al-Bashir met here today with the visiting former U.S. President
Jimmy Carter on arrangements for the signing of a peace agreement
due on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese "Om Durman" radio reported that emerging from the
meeting, Carter said he and Al-Bashir discussed the progress of
the peace process in Sudan. The talks also dealt with the issue of
peace between Sudan and its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese government is scheduled to sign a peace agreement
Monday with the leaders of four small rebel factions. But the
largest anti-government group operating in southern Sudan, the
Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA), has refused to join the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The radio report quoted Sudanese Ambassador to Washington Mahdi
Ibrahim, who attended the Bashir-Carter meeting, as saying that
"the talks dealt with the prospective admission of other parties
to the peace agreement, the attainment of the cherished peace in
southern Sudan and making it an example to be followed in the
African continent which had suffered from conflicts and external
interference."
</P>
<P>
The radio reported that Carter also met with Sudanese Foreign
Minister Ali Osman Mohammed Taha and Dr Hassan Abdulla Al Turabi,
speaker of the Sudanese National Assembly, on the preparatory
steps to sign the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging in the war-torn country since the
beginning of this year between the government forces on the one
side and the northern opposition parties of the National
Democratic Alliance and rebel troops of the SPLA on the other in
the Sudanese eastern and southern border areas.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Carter arrived in Khartoum Saturday on a week-long trip
which will also take him to Uganda, Eritrea and Ethiopia, three
Sudanese neighbors that have been charged of supporting the
Sudanese rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
