<HEADLINE> Fire Under Control in Flooded US Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters in Grand Forks,
North Dakota of the United States, have contained a fire that
destroyed at least six buildings on three different blocks
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The blaze was still burning at midday today, but was expected
to be completely out by this evening, said news reports.
</P>
<P>
As floodwaters hampered conventional fire-fighting efforts,
fire crews assisted by U.S. Coast Guard personnel and other
agencies used fire-bombing planes to dump chemicals on the blaze.
</P>
<P>
Fire equipment was also brought in to pump floodwaters from the
overflowing Red River onto the burning buildings. Grand Forks Air
Force Base sent in a floating pumper truck.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of injuries, but concerns about
structural safety were keeping crews from searching the damaged
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Several other buildings were damaged by the fire in addition to
the six that were totally destroyed, but early damage assessments
were still under way.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire, which began burning at about 4 p.m.
Saturday, has not been determined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
