<HEADLINE> Funds-Raising Key to Liberian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- How to raise the 13 million U.S.
dollars needed for the May 30 Liberian elections has now become a
key issue in ensuring final peace and democracy in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency of Nigeria said in a report today
that a detailed budget for the elections has been submitted to
general Sani Abacha, the Nigerian head of state and chairman of
the west African Economic Community of West African States
(ECOMAS), the peace-maker in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
However, the report indicated that raising of the fund has now
become a major task fore the ECOMAS leaders, who are already
having difficulties in maintaining the 10,000-odd peace-keeping
force in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, as well as some members of the
international community had indicated their intention to help
finance the elections.
</P>
<P>
However, one month to the elections, none of them have
redeemed their pledges, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Gambari, Nigerian's permanent representative to the
United Nations and the newly-re-elected chairman of the UN
special committee on peace-keeping operations, had last week
called on the international society to redeem their pledges to
fund the Liberian elections.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, officials at the Nigerian Ministry of
Foreign Affairs are optimistic that the ECOMAS leaders will rise
to the challenge, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing the light at the end of the tunnel and it would
be risky to lose the present momentum in the implementation of
the peace plan," an official said. 
</P>
