<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-20 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Crisis Not Over Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu had a temporary sigh of relief tonight following the
state prosecution's decision to drop indictment against him over
the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
But for the near future, the government crisis will continue
looming large in Netanyahu's mind and he has to fight the
possible defections within his cabinet and the legal challenge
from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein announced this evening
that he and State Attorney Edana Arbel decided not to accept the
 police recommendation of indictments against Netanyahu and
Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, citing lack of sufficient
evidence that can stand the rigors of the court.
</P>
<P>
Only Shas party leader Aryeh Deri was charged with extortion
and fraud in pushing the government to appoint former Jerusalem
lawyer Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general in January in hope to
obtain a plea bargain deal in his bribery trial.
</P>
<P>
The acquittal of charges and the relatively soft language
used by the attorney-general on Netanyahu's role in the Bar-On
affair in fact virtually averted the immediate downfall of the
Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Is was almost certain that if Netanyahu is indicted, he would
be forced to resign to pave the way for new elections. And if
attorney-general's report on the affair contained harsh criticism
could also bring down the government due to possible subsequent
cabinet defections.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still not completely clear now that if
Netanyahu has overcome the crisis to survive, because some
ministers will carefully read the 80-page prosecution's final
report on Bar-On affair.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein in fact did not clear all the cloud over
Netanyahu's head for his role in the short-lived appointment of
Bar-On. The attorney-general did note that "suspicions and
doubts" still existed over Netanyahu's role in the controversial
appointment, and the main reason to drop indictment was only for
the lack of solid evidence.
</P>
<P>
So the prosecution's report is still wide open to different
interpretation by the whole society, and crucial for some
ministers who are described as "the weak links" in the
coalition. Some of them might still think that the current
government's credibility and image have been severely damaged,
thus losing the public trust and moral ground to continue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, even when local media predicted no indictment
to be filed against Netanyahu, several cabinet ministers were
reportedly considering leaving the coalition: they included
Likud's Finance Minister Dan Meridor and Communications Minister
Limor Livnat, Yisrael Baaliya's Trade Minister Natan Sharansky
and Absorption Minister Yuli Edelstein, and The Third Way's
Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
Both Yisrael Baaliya and The Third Way will hold urgent
meetings tonight to decide their future participation in the
current government. Netanyahu and his aides have been trying
hard since the weekend to prevent cabinet defections, holding
dialogues with both party leaderships.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, if the coalition loses its majority of 61
seats in the 120-seat Knesset (Parliament), it should resign to
pave the way for holding new elections within 60 days. The
Likud-led coalition holds 66 Knesset seats, including Yisrael
Baaliya's 7 seats and The Third Way's 4 seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leading opposition parties Labor and Meretz have
planned to press on with their campaign to topple the government
by petitioning the High Court of Justice to overrule the
attorney-general's decision not to indict Netanyahu and other
officials. This will be long legal battle that might continue
haunting the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
So today's decision by the state prosecution to refrain from
filing charges against him only provided Netanyahu a very short
sigh of relieve, and the crisis of survival is still lurking
somewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-20 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Calls for Pooled Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today urged exhaustive efforts to salvage the faltering
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The stalled Mideast peace should be salvaged and should be out
of the present bottleneck for the good of all parties," Moussa
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He called for holding all necessary contacts to rescue the
peace march and to return it back to its right track in line with
the principles of reaching a balanced peace.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the message he received from Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat today, in which Arafat gave a full assessment of the
current situation of the Mideast peace process, Moussa said that
it comes within the context of the Egyptian-Palestinian
coordination to save the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
"Intensive contacts are under way with the parties concerned,"
Moussa added, in a reference to his recent meetings in Malta with
European, Palestinian and Israeli officials as well as the
contacts made by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's Political
Advisor Osama el-Baz in Washington.
</P>
<P>
However, he lamented that these contacts have not yet yielded
any results.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, siding with the Palestinians, has intensified its
diplomatic drive in a bid to stop the Israeli Jewish settlement
construction in disputed East Jerusalem and revive the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has insisted that
Arafat stop the riots and crack down on militants. Arafat, in
turn, has said that Israel must stop the settlement construction
in East Jerusalem and in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's adviser Nabil Abu Redina said today that the
Palestinians have made no decision on resuming security
cooperation with Israel, despite Israel's claim that it has
secured Palestinian promise to curb violence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat broke contacts with Israeli security forces in
mid-March, angered by Israeli Jewish home-building in East
Jerusalem. The security cooperation had been a success of
Israeli-Palestinian peacemaking, and was deemed vital for foiling
suicide attacks on Israeli targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
