<HEADLINE> Ex-Irish PM Allegedly Involved in Bribery Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Irish Prime Minister
Charles Haughey is alleged to get involved into a bribery case in
which he has received more than 1.6 million U.S. dollars from a
department store millionaire, said reports from Dublin, capital of
Ireland, today.
</P>
<P>
An inquiry into charges that millionaire Ben Dunne paid
millions of dollars to Irish politicians opened Monday, and
Haughey, prime minister four times between 1979 and 1992, will be
named as a recipient.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is likely to stoke the fires under a
smouldering election campaign pitting Prime Minister John Bruton's
three-party coalition against the Fianna Fail opposition which
Haughey once led.
</P>
<P>
According to The Sunday Times, Haughey received money through
intermediaries in 1989. The money, paid in several instalments,
ended up in an account in the Cayman Islands, which has strict
secrecy laws protecting account holders
</P>
<P>
However, Haughey, a veteran politician in the country, has
denied his involvement in the scandal which burst last December
although Irish Transport Minister Michael Lowry has resigned after
admitting that Dunne paid for a quarter-million pound house
renovation.
</P>
<P>
The scandal raised calls for an overhaul of the way political
parties are funded in Ireland and more openness in the links
between big business and politics.
</P>
<P>
Dunne is expected to be among the first called to give evidence
when the tribunal of inquiry begins at Dublin Castle Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
