<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-20 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Netanyahu Escapes Indictment Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Attorney-General
Elyakim Rubinstein announced today that no indictment would be
filed against Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu for his
involvement in the Bar-On scandal, citing lack of sufficient
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, Rubinstein described the
"Bar-On for Hebron" scandal as a very difficult and
complicated matter. He said he and State Attorney Edana Arbel
decided to close the case against Netanyahu and Justice
Minister Tzahi Hanegbi for reason of insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
The police investigators probing the Bar-On affair last week
recommended indicting Netanyahu, Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime Minister's
Office Director-General Avigdor Liberman with breach of trust
and fraud for their involvement in the short-lived appointment
of former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general
in January.
</P>
<P>
But Rubinstein said there was sufficient evidence to indict
Shas party leader Aryeh Deri for extortion and fraud in
pushing for Bar-On's appointment in order to serve his private
interests.
</P>
<P>
According to the original report which exposed the Bar-On
affair by the state television Channel I, Deri reportedly
conditioned Shas' support to the Hebron agreement on the
Bar-On's appointment in hope to obtain a plea bargain deal
in his bribery trial.
</P>
<P>
No decision was made on the police charges against
Prime Minister's Office Director-General Avigdor Liberman,
and the investigation on his role would continue, Rubinstein
said.
</P>
<P>
The tone of Rubinstein's statements was relatively soft on
Netanyahu, who he said that indeed suggested Bar-On's
appointment in order to appease his coalition ally Deri. But
the attorney-general pointed out that no solid evidence had
been obtained to prove that Deri's threats had reached
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"After closing the deliberation, we drew the conclusion that
we do not have sufficient and physical evidence with
sufficient grounds for proving that indeed there is criminal
offense on the part of the prime minister," Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
Arbel released a 80-page detailed report on the State
Attorney's Office's reviewing of the police recommendations and
materials. The language used in her report is regarded as
crucial to Netanyahu who is striving to avert the collapse
of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
In his immediate reaction, Netanyahu welcomed the state
prosecution's decision, saying he had been vindicated. He
described himself as the victim of the de-legitematizing campaign
launched by his political opponents and the media, particularly
the Channel I Television which first exposed the Bar-On
scandal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the private television Channel 2, Netanyahu
blasted the Bar-On affair as part of the leftists' campaign
aimed at bringing down his elected government, simply because
of its policies of building in Har Homa, opposing division
of Jerusalem, rejecting a Palestinian state and refusing return
of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the nation to look forward, Netanyahu denied he
had committed any crime though he might have made a mistake.
He called for the public's trust and support to him in
order to build a better future.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Labor's leader Shimon Peres said attorney-general's
ruling proved two things: though there was no enough evidence
to bring Netanyahu to trial, but there was reason and
evidence to put Netanyahu before the public for judgement. He
predicted that Netanyahu could not go on in the shadow of
one of the most serious accusations.
</P>
<P>
Leading candidate for Labor's leadership Ehud Barak called on
every honest citizen to question about the moral authority of
Netanyahu, who he said only escaped an indictment because of
insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition Meretz leader Rossi Sarid said he would
appeal to the High Court of Justice to overturn the state
prosecution's decision on indictments against Netanyahu and
Hanegbi. He believed that the prime minister would find it
difficult to function.
</P>
<P>
Despite the escape from an indictment, Netanyahu still faces
a crisis of survival as some ministers might consider leaving
the government, whose image and credibility have been seriously
damaged by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that the likely defectors within the
cabinet included Likud's Finance Minister Dan Meridor and
Communications Minister Limor Livnat, Yisrael Baaliya's Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky and Absorption Minister Yuli Edelstein,
and The Third Way's Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
Yisrael Baaliya and The Third Way are holding emergency
meetings late tonight to discuss their future participation in
the current government. Their decision would be crucial to the
fate of the Netanyahu government, which holds only a majority
of 66 seats in the 120-seat Knesset (Parliament), including
Yisrael Baaliya's seven seats and The Third Way's four seats.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, new elections will be held within 60
days if the government loses its 61 seat majority at the
Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
