<HEADLINE> OIC Chief Arrives in Egypt on Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Izzidine Laraki, secretary
general of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC)
arrived here today starting his four-nation tour designed to show
solidarity with the Arab and Islamic countries' stance on the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which is the first of its kind to be paid by Laraki
since he became new OIC chief early this year, will also take him
to Palestinian self-rule Gaza, Jordan and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, the Moroccan-origin Laraki said his visit is
aimed at expressing the organization's support for Arab and
Islamic efforts exerted within the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the peace process should be based on agreements
concluded by the Palestinians and Israelis as well as on the
Palestinian rights to establish their own state, with Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
"The OIC is exerting strenuous efforts to back the Palestinian
cause in general and to defend Jerusalem in particular through
contacts with other organizations and countries," according to
Laraki.
</P>
<P>
The 52-member OIC has called for Islamic countries to
reconsider their ties with Israel at its March summit meeting in
Islamabad, Pakistan, in light of Israel's settlement activities
in Jerusalem, a city holy to Muslims, Christians and Jews alike.
</P>
<P>
A special OIC Jerusalem Committee held in Rabat, Morocco, also
condemned the Israeli decision to build new Jewish settlement in
disputed East Jerusalem, a move that has now stalled the Mideast
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
