<HEADLINE> Polish Police, Soccer Body to Crack on Soccer Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Polish police will join hands with
the country's soccer body to crack down on rising soccer violence
after a recent clash left 37 officers injured in a Warsaw stadium.
</P>
<P>
A police spokeman said on Monday that police arrested 76 people
after rioting broke out between rival fans of first division sides
Polonia and Legia, both based in Warsaw, at Polonia's home ground
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Warsaw police have asked the provincial
governor to temporarily close the stadium.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the riot, the Polish Soccer Association said it
will require all soccer fans accompanying their teams on away
games to carry identity cards.
</P>
<P>
Those who have involved in soccer hooliganism will be barred
from the stadiums, the association said.
</P>
<P>
The soccer body added that soccer teams will also be held
responsible for their supporters' behavior and could even be
barred from competing in European cup matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
