<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MILF-Held Areas Not Separate Territory: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Renato de Villa reiterated today that the areas held by the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in the southern Philippines are
not separate territory.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely out of the question to grant any separate
territory to those who disagree with the government," de Villa
stressed in an interview with the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
De Villa said the government allows the MILF liberal access to
some areas in central Mindanao, but that does not mean "we
recognize these areas as belonging to them."
</P>
<P>
Renewed tit-for-tat fighting has continued between the MILF and
the government forces in Mindanao island, the southern
Philippines, since early last week.
</P>
<P>
The military confirmed earlier that as of Sunday, the renewed
fighting had killed 25 MILF rebels and 2 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
It is unclear whether the fighting will derail the scheduled
third-round of low-level peace talks between the MILF and the
government, which have been delayed several times.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the MILF and the government agreed to
resume low-level peace talks to discuss issues regarding a
comprehensive ceasefire between the two sides in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has set as preconditions for reaching a comprehensive
truce the government's recognition of the MILF-controlled areas
and the government troops' withdrawal from these areas.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), was not part of a peace deal signed last September
by the MNLF and the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest Muslim rebel group in the
country, with an estimated membership of 12,000. The group has
sought to establish an independent Islamic state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0063 </DOCNO>
