<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House to Urge Cut on Okinawa Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives, the
lower house of the Japanese Diet (parliament), will urge the
government to cut the U.S. bases in Okinawa, Kyodo News Service
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The demand is expected to be made in a resolution ready for a
vote at a plenary session of the lower house Tuesday, Kyodo said.
</P>
<P>
A final draft of the resolution says lawmakers believe that the
government's policies have been quite insufficient for the
"excessive burdens" placed by U.S. military bases on Okinawa, the
news service said.
</P>
<P>
The draft urges the government to make utmost efforts to
consolidate, realign and reduce U.S. bases in Okinawa and to
proceed with consultations with the United States on military
postures including the U.S. forces structure in the Asian-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
The draft also calls for "drastic reforms" to help develop
Okinawa's economy to turn the island prefecture into "an
economically and culturally prominent foothold for international
exchanges," Kyodo said.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa is home to 75 percent of all U.S. military facilities
in Japan. More than half of the 47,000 U.S. troops in Japan are
stationed on the island.
</P>
<P>
A government-proposed bill to revise legislation to allow the
continued compulsory lease of land for use by the U.S. military
was passed by the Diet last week, bringing protests from both
local authorities and residents in Okinawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
