<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petitions Filed Against Decision not to Indict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Five petitions were presented
to Israel's High Court of Justice today against the state
prosecution's decision not to indict Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu over the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
Among those submitting the petitions included four opposition
lawmakers: Meretz leader Yossi Sarid and Labor's Yossi Beilin,
Ofer Pines and Yona Yahav. A watchdog group The Movement for
Quality Government (MQG) also presented a petition over the
decision not to charge Netanyahu and Justice Minister Tzahi
Hanegbi.
</P>
<P>
They argued that the decision by Attorney-General Elyakim
Rubinstein and State Attorney Edana Arbel not to indict
Netanyahu and Hanegbi for their involvement in the Bar-On
scandal was highly unreasonable since police investigators
recommended charging them with breach of trust and fraud.
</P>
<P>
Sarid, Beilin and Yahav requested the court to try Hanegbi
and Liberman, director-general of Prime Minister's Office, while
Pines also called for Netanyahu's resignation.
</P>
<P>
The MQG asked the court to suspend Hanegbi and Liberman from
their official positions and order the release of the 900-page
materials compiled by the police team investigating the Bar-On
scandal.
</P>
<P>
The high court is expected to hear the petitions at the
beginning of next month. It is premature to predict the likely
outcome of the legal battle, but the court has set several
precedents in overturning the attorney-general's decision not to
accept police recommendations of indictments against government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein and Arbel announced Sunday not to indict Netanyahu
and Hanegbi, citing the lack of solid evidence in the police
recommendations. But they admitted that deep suspicions existed
over the prime minister's role in the short-lived appointment of
former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On as the attorney-general in
January.
</P>
<P>
Only Shas leader Aryeh Deri will be charged with extortion
and fraud in pushing for Bar-On's appointment in the hope to
gain a plea bargain deal in his future bribery trial. Deri was
suspected of threatening to vote against the Hebron agreement by
his party if Bar-On was not appointed.
</P>
<P>
In reaction Sunday night, Netanyahu blasted the scandal,
exposed by the state television Channel I, as a conspiracy by
the leftist camp and the pro-leftist media to "overturn the
voters' verdict" in the last elections by toppling his
government.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted having made a mistake in the Bar-On
affair despite denying any crime committed. He promised to
broaden the future process of decision-making by setting up a
ministerial committee to oversee future appointments of
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that, although Netanyahu has now averted a
government crisis, the shadow of the Bar-On scandal has not been
cleared, and it will continue haunting his government once the
high court begins the hearing of the opposition's petitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
