<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Japanese Automakers Expand Exports in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Four of Japan's top five automakers
boosted motor vehicle exports in fiscal 1996 ending March 31,
supported by the yen's recent weakness against the U.S. dollar,
the companies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports of Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's leading car maker,
jumped 12.4 percent to 1.31 million vehicles, marking the first
year-on-year rise in six years, a Toyota spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The company attributed the export growth to brisk demand for
such sport-utility vehicles as the 4Runner and the Rav4 to the
United States, as well as increased shipments to European and
Middle Eastern nations.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the U.S. accounted for 460,361 in the fiscal year,
up 12.5 percent, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Exports for Nissan Motor Co. rose 0.8 percent to 598,000, the
first year-on-year rise in five years. Honda Motor Co. and Mazda
Motor Corp. saw exports pick up 6.7 percent and 8.6 percent to
407,000 and 463,000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Motors Corp., whose exports dropped 5.0 percent to
462,000, was the only company among the nation's top five
automakers to fail to bolster its exports in the latest reporting
year.
</P>
<P>
A weak yen makes car manufacturers and other Japanese exporters
more competitive by allowing them to lower prices on their goods
sold abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
