<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Government Urged to Arrest High Maternal Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government was
urged today to take measures to arrest the high maternal mortality
rate in the country.
</P>
<P>
Local mothers running a risk of dying 100 times higher than
their counterparts in the rest of the world urgently require
improved maternal health services at the community and first
referral levels, said professor Sadqa Jaffery, a senior
gynecologist in Karachi, according to a report by the Associated
Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"Improved prenatal and delivery care for all women, supported
by appropriate family planning services, must be among the top
priorities of our policy makers," she said.
</P>
<P>
Jaffery also called on the government to improve the
socio-economic and political status for women.
</P>
<P>
"There is need to create awareness and build commitment among
decision makers to ensure that appropriate programs are launched
and sustained," she said.
</P>
<P>
She cited hemorrhage, pregnancy related hypertension,
infection, obstructed labor and unsafe abortion as some of the
major medical causes of maternal deaths in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The problem stems not only from inadequate health services but
from the social, cultural and economic environment in which women
live," she observed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
