<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 46th PATA Annual Meeting Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The 46th annual conference of
Pacific Asia Travel Association (PATA) opened in Beijing today,
hailed by an inaugural speech from Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
About 1,800 people attended today's opening ceremony of the
meeting, considered to be the leading and largest international
tourism meeting ever held on China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that in recent years, Asia and Pacific regions
have been witnessing rapid expansion in tourism and their
positions in the world's tourism industry have become more and
more impressive.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of the Asia-Pacific, China is ready to make
positive contributions to the development of tourism in this
region and the world at large," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the 21st century, the tourism industry has broad
development prospects and will eventually become an important
motivating force behind the world's economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li told participants that China, with rich tourism resources,
has had an annual average growth rate of ten percent in economic
development since 1978, which has in turn laid a solid foundation
for the boom of the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
China's stable political situation, sustained economic
development, a prosperous economy, the Chinese government's firm
implementation of opening-up drive and its active development of
relations with other countries of the world have also created
favorable conditions for the development of tourism in the country.
</P>
<P>
China had 51 million overseas tourists and earned over 10
billion U.S. dollars from related services in 1996. It also
reported 640 million domestic tourists who spent 160 billion yuan
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Li said that as the living standards of the Chinese people
continues to improve, the outbound trips of Chinese citizens will
also increase year by year.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government places great importance on the
development of the tourism industry and will list accelerating the
development of tourism as an important part of its social and
economic development plan for the 1996-2010 period.
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Luo Gan also delivered a speech at today's
opening session, and a number of Chinese artists performed.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Drysdale, PATA chairman, also briefed the crowd on the
tourism developments in the world and the Asia-Pacific region, and
reviewed the work PATA has so far done to advance the growth of
the sector.
</P>
<P>
Lakshman Ratnapala, PATA president and CEO, presented the
PATA '96 annual work report at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1952 and Now headquartered in San Francisco, PATA is
an influential non-governmental international tourism organization
aimed at advancing the tourism industry in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The China National Tourism Administration joined PATA in 1993
and became an official member. A total of 35 other Chinese
tourism-related businesses have also joined PATA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
