<HEADLINE> 5 Percent Adults Using Heroin in Pakistan: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- About five percent of adult
population in Pakistan are using drugs and an estimated fifty tons
of opium is smuggled into the country for processing into heroin
for domestic use, according to a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has became the worst victim of drug trade in South
Asia and has the largest heroin consumer market in the South-West
Asia region, said the report on Human Development in South Asia
1997.
</P>
<P>
The report was prepared by former finance minister Dr. Mahbub
ul Haq and the financial support for the report was provided by
the United Nations and several bilateral donors, particularly
Canada, Denmark, Netherlands, Norway and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that almost 80 per cent of the opium processed
in Pakistan comes from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
India , Bangladesh, Nepal and Maldives are also facing drug
problem as the drug abuse is growing rapidly in the region, said
the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister Denies Plan to Increase Gas Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today denied a report that he had planned to raise gasoline tax in
the coming summer, describing it as "pure speculation."
</P>
<P>
Waigel made the remarks in response to a report in the Bild
daily, which said that the minister planned to increase the tax on
unleaded gasoline by 18 pfennigs (about 0.11 U.S. dollar) from the
current 98 pfennigs (0.57 dollar) per liter from July 1.
</P>
<P>
This move would boost the state revenues by 15 billion marks
(8.8 billion dollars) annually, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
An increased gasoline tax has been urged by Germany's main
opposition Social Democratic Party, known as SPD in German, to
support Chancellor Helmut Kohl's proposed cuts on income tax.
</P>
<P>
But Kohl's government intended to raise value added tax (VAT)
by one percentage point to 16 percent, which would also add about
15 billion marks (8.8 billion dollars) annually to the state
coffers.
</P>
<P>
The federal chancellor was due to meet with SPD leaders on
Wednesday to negotiate a compromise on tax reform legislation. The
SPD controls Bundesrat, the upper house of German parliament.
</P>
<P>
The gasoline tax in Germany was last raised by 16 pfennigs
(0.10 dollar) in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
