<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Continue Producing "Timor" National Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia today decided to
continue producing the 'Timor' national car despite the fact that
Japan had officially brought its complaints to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) panel.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after President Soeharto met with several
cabinet ministers at the Bina Graha Presidential Office,
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Japan decided to ask the WTO to create a panel to
rule on Japan's complaints against Indonesia's national car
policy.
</P>
<P>
The move came as the two countries failed to make progress in
bilateral talks during which Japan insisted on action to redress
discriminatory car-making practices under the Indonesian national
car policy.
</P>
<P>
Under the Indonesian car policy, domestic car makers can enjoy
tax exemptions on condition they raise their local content ratios
to 60 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture established by Pt. Timor Nasional, controlled
by President Soeharto's youngest son Hutomo Mandala Putra, and Kia
Corp. of South Korea is the only company qualified for tax
exemption privileges in the country.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is disappointed over Japan's move, Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
The president also decided to stop the bilateral discussions
between Indonesia and Japan on the national car, Moerdiono added.
</P>
<P>
"Should the WTO panel discuss the national car, the WTO will
likely make its decision on the national car in 1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the European Union also raised their
complaints over the Indonesian national car policy.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said Indonesia now capable of producing aircraft and
ships, will go ahead with the national car.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
