<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Monetary Authority Strengthens Ties with Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) and the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) have
agreed that the Central Moneymarkets Unit (CMU) of the HKMA will
join hands with RBA's Reserve Bank Information and Transfer System
(RITS).
</P>
<P>
An HKMA spokesman said that it is a step towards closer
bilateral relations between Australian and Hong Kong financial
systems.
</P>
<P>
RBA will explore with the HKMA further reciprocal arrangements
to extend more widely the benefits that such co-operative
arrangements can provide.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, CMU is the central clearing and
settlement system for debt securities in Hong Kong and RITS is a
similar system for Australian government paper.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations believe that this bilateral linkage will
broaden the investor base of the debt markets in Hong Kong and
Australia by making cross system trading and holding of securities
much easier.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the agreement was reached at a meeting
between Joseph Yam, chief executive of HKMA, and Ian Macfarlane,
governor of RBA in Sydney at the second bilateral annual meeting
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings have been established in the context of
fostering enhanced mutual cooperation between the two banks.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, a range of subjects of mutual interest was
discussed, including regional central bank cooperation, recent
economic developments and banking supervision policy and practice,
the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
