<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Diplomat: Kazakhstan Active in U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan has been active in
the United Nations since gaining independence and the world body's
membership five years ago, a senior Kazak diplomat has said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan has become an inseparable part of the international
community, the country's permanent representative to the United
Nations was quoted as saying by a published report available here
today.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, Akmaral Khaidaidarkyzy Arystanbekova, told weekly
Panorama magazine that Kazakhstan's foreign policy of maintaining
world peace has been recognized and backed by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In nuclear disarmament, Arystanbekova said, Kazakhstan has
signed the first-phase strategic arms reduction treaty, the
non-proliferation treaty and the comprehensive test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
In addition, by destroying some of its nuclear weapons and
transferring all others out of its territory, the former Soviet
republic has declared itself a nuclear-free nation, she said.
</P>
<P>
Among its major efforts to ensure regional security, she said,
Kazakhstan initiated in 1995 a mechanism for consultations and the
building-up of mutual trust among countries in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The country, together with Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan, has also
mobilized a peace-keeping force for the entire region, and pushed
forward the peace process in Tajikistan, Arystanbekova noted.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, she said, Kazakhstan is poised to play a more
active role in U.N-sponsored activities, and to cooperate with
other U.N. members to enhence its own international status.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan joined the United Nations in March 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
