<HEADLINE> Dhaka Sees Great Potentials of South Asia Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah
Ams Kibria has stated that the South Asia Development Triangle
(SADT) had tremendous opportunities for reaching benefits to the
people of the region, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a preparatory meeting on the SADT initiated by the
World Bank Sunday, he said that the people in this region would be
immensely benefited with this cooperation while he also warned not
to mix the emotional issues with the economic issues.
</P>
<P>
The so-called SADT, which was proposed last year by Dhaka to be
constituted with Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal and eastern and
north-eastern parts of India, has a population of 500 million,
two-thirds of whom live on less than one U.S. dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's main opposition party has been opposing the
formation of the SADT, alleging that the sovereignty of Bangladesh
would be threatened if the transit facilities were offered to
India.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's resident mission chief Pierre Landell Mills
also emphasized the need of solving the political problems, saying
the future of the transboundary cooperation would largely depend
on the effective solution of the political problems.
</P>
<P>
He urged the professionals to take the initiative to develop
understanding among the political leadership regarding the
opportunities that "now exist in this region".  
</P>
</TEXT>
