<HEADLINE> Australia to Assess Wool Marketing on Overseas Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Wool Council of Australia
(WCA) has decided to send a team to travel to China, the United
Kingdom, Italy and the United states to make an independent
assessment of overall demand conditions for wool and the
sustainability of recent price movement.
</P>
<P>
WCA president Rod Thirkell-Johnston said today that the mission
would speak to processors, retailers and advertising agents to
evaluate the success in overseas promotion programs, made by its
international marketing body, International wool Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Auction prices reached their highest level in more than 18
months last week, with the eastern market indicator closing at 640
Australian cents (499 US cents) per kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
"There is a special interest in gauging the outlook on apparel
demand in Europe which, with the exception of the United Kingdom,
has been subdued to recessed over the last several years, while
the Asian leg will look at growth prospects in emerging markets
and China," the WCA president said in a statement.  
</P>
