<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Population Control, Hard Nut to Crack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- While giving top priority to
reviving the depressed national economy, the government led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif is paying greater attention to
curtailing the country's ever growing population.
</P>
<P>
The Nawaz government, which came to power in mid February, is
now formulating a population control strategy in a bid to raise
the overall living standard of the people.
</P>
<P>
A result-oriented approach is the key to success in population
programs in Pakistan, Minister for Population Welfare Abida
Hussain said recently at a meeting on the country's population
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Nawaz government, which has vowed to make Pakistan an
"Asian Tiger," will formulate a viable strategy to ensure
effective implementation of policies on population control, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Population experts here believe that fast population growth, an
acute chronic problem, is the most crucial factor retarding the
development of the country, and it may well cast a blight on all
ideas envisaged by the Nawaz government to turn the country into a
welfare state.
</P>
<P>
As a result of a galloping annual growth rate of about 3
percent, Pakistan, with a population of around 140 million, has
now moved up to the rank of the world's seventh most populous
nation from the ninth position it occupied two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
If the present growth rate continues, the country will have
more people than the United States and Indonesia by the middle of
the next century. Pakistan might then become the third largest
country in the world in terms of population after China and India.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated annual increase of 3 million, the country
will find it very difficult to provide its people with food,
water, jobs, education and medicines from its limited resources
since every effort and scheme to develop additional resources to
improve the lot of the people is being outstripped by a faster
growing population.
</P>
<P>
Population experts here are of the view that Pakistan's present
gloomy state of the economy, law and order problem, corruption,
illiteracy, poverty and scarcity of essential food items are
directly attributable to excessive population growth.
</P>
<P>
The main cause of Pakistan's high population growth is widely
believed to be the high fertility rate which goes with poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to the Economic Survey of the 1995-1996 fiscal year,
Pakistan's total fertility rate -- the average number of children
a woman can expect to have -- is 5.9 and infant mortality is 95
per 1,000 births.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that Pakistan's galloping population
growth is closely linked with the relatively low contraceptive
prevalence rate, which shows that family planning and reproductive
health services are still not available to, or used by, the
majority of people who need or want them.
</P>
<P>
The recent Contraceptive Prevalence Survey by the United
Nations Fund for Population Activities showed that contraceptive
use in Pakistan increased from 11.8 percent in 1990-1991 to 17.8
percent in 1994-1995. But it is still the lowest in the South
Asian region. Much remains to be done to raise the level to where
it can make a significant impact on population growth.
</P>
<P>
In view of the alarming estimates of Pakistan's population,
population control is the need of the hour in the country, yet it
is not an easy job for the Nawaz government.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that population growth can only be brought down
through the provision of family planning and reproductive health
services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Mobilizes Youngsters to Help Maintain Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Macao has started a special course
for the young people to mobilize them to help crack down on rising
crimes in the territory.
</P>
<P>
The "Macao Youth Anti-Crime Course," which began last week and
will last for six months, is aimed at improving the youngsters'
sense of responsibility for social justice and caring for others,
said organizers of the movement.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 students and youngsters have joined in the
course, co-sponsored by the Macao Security Department and the
Macao Students' Union.
</P>
<P>
Apart from lectures on ways of contacting police department and
on traffic control, they will visit police school, headquarters of
marine police and fire squad. They will also learn ways of
emergency treatment in case of injuries.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipate that the course will help students gain a better
 knowledge of crimes, improve their self-discipline and relations
between police and civilians," said a top executive of the Macao
Students' Union.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the youngsters will enhance their sense of social
responsibility through the course, thus contributing partly to
maintaining a good social order," said the executive.
</P>
<P>
A wave of gang-related killings and injury cases occurred in
Macao over the past months, triggering increasing worries in the
territory. Juvenile delinquency, in particular, has risen sharply
over the last few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
