<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Confident Of Winning Coming Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
said today that he is confident of winning the coming election on
May 1st.
</P>
<P>
Major, however, admitted in an interview with the Times that he
was "baffled" by the opinion polls showing a big Labor lead which
"bear no relationship to what I fell going round the country".
</P>
<P>
Dismissing protests about the Conservative Party advertisement
showing a small Labor leader Tony Blair on the knee of a giant
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Major said "Politics has become so
pompous", describing the "rough and tumble of politics" as part of
its charm.
</P>
<P>
He said: "If Tony Blair were Prime Minister and he asked my
advice about how to handle European negotiations, he could have it
in complete privacy and in complete frankness."
</P>
<P>
Major said other European leaders were pushing the national
patience in more than one country to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed for the first time that Conservative members of
the parliament would probably be offered a free vote on any
decision to take Britain into a single currency.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he is "sick and tired" of the fact that
whenever he tells truth in Brussels, it is portrayed as "poor old
Britain, isolated again, taking a different Eurosceptic line."
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing Eurosceptic about pointing out that this
institution is creaking ... it is pushing the national states too
far and it will break up ... if it carries on as it is going," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
