<HEADLINE> Kenya, Ethiopia to Continue Border Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan and Ethiopian government
officials are scheduled to meet today in Embu, northern Kenya,
for further talks on last month's border incidents, according to
a Daily Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said the new round of border talks would
begin in Illet in Marsabit where the incidents occurred,
resulting in the killing of 66 Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the two-day meeting would discuss the possibility
of the Ethiopian government to compensate Kenya for the losses
during the attacks in the border area by armed gangsters from the
Ethiopian side.
</P>
<P>
During the attacks, about 80 people, including 17 Kenyan
security officers and 16 armed bandits, were killed when
Shangilla and Armakolle bandits attacked the area bordering
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, a Kenyan delegation led by the Rift Valley
Provincial Commissioner Yusuf Haji visited Addis Ababa, Ethiopia,
to press for compensation for life and property losses during the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Haji said that the Ethiopians were very
sympathetic and regretted the incidents, adding that both sides
had agreed to work together to stamp out lawlessness in the
border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
