<HEADLINE> Stock Market Index Conference Held in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- About 150 investors, analysts
and regulators today attended the International Statistical
Institute Cutting Edge Conference on Stock Market Indexes and
Index Derivatives Trading and shared views with many renowned
speakers from the world on the latest developments in the field.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the conference, Alexander S.K. Au,
vice-chairman and chief executive of Hang Seng Bank, said the
development of stock market indices has been accompanied by growth
in index derivatives trading.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We believe that the conference will help enhance Hong
Kong's reputation as a major international financial center and as
China's largest financial center."
</P>
<P>
He said that such derivatives play an integral role in the
development of financial markets, which in turn is an important
factor in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the average daily turnover of Hang Seng Index
Futures at the Futures Exchange amounted to 11 billion HK dollars
(1.42 billion U.S. dollars), which almost double the average daily
turnover of 6 billion HK dollars (774.2 million U.S. dollars) at
the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The average number of futures contracts traded on the Futures
Exchange is 21,046 per day and that of futures on options
contracts amounts to 5,195 per day, representing a notional value
of 1.9 billion HK dollars (245.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Rafael S.Y. Hui, secretary for financial services, said, "The
conference is certainly opportune and innovative. The
availability of financial market must be a key ingredient for any
product that the market intends to develop."
</P>
<P>
The conference focused on the latest trends in index
construction and maintenance, the latest derivatives trading
strategies, their impact on the underlying stock markets and the
current regulatory environment.
</P>
<P>
The one-and-a-half day conference is jointly organized by HSI
Services Limited, the International Statistical Institute, the
Census and Statistics Department of the Hong Kong Government and
the Hong Kong Baptist University.  
</P>
</TEXT>
