<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gujral Sworn in as India's 12th Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Newly elected leader of the
13-party United Front (UF) and External Affairs Minister I. K.
Gujral was sworn in by President S. D. Sharma as India's 12th
prime minister here today, ending 22 days of political uncertainty
following the withdrawal of support of the Congress party to the
UF government headed by Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
Gujral retained all the 34 ministers of the Deve Gowda
government except the four ministers from the Tamil Maanila
Congress (TMC) and one minister from Janata Dal, the biggest
constituent of the UF.
</P>
<P>
The TMC has decided to keep away from the new government while
the surprise exclusion of Food and Civil Supplies Minister D. P.
Yadav from the new cabinet was reportedly related to internal
conflicts of the Janata Dal.
</P>
<P>
The retention of the Gowda government ministers was based on a
decision taken by top Front leaders late last night to send a
signal that the coalition UF stands for unity, continuity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Of the 34 ministers, 16 are of cabinet rank while the rest are
ministers of state. The new prime minister said here today that he
would undertake expansion of his 35-member council of ministers
but declined to specify when he would effect it. He expressed the
hope that the TMC would be persuaded to participate in his
government. The TMC was reportedly unhappy with the attitude of
some UF constituents towards it during the race for premiership.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen soon after the swearing-in ceremony, Gujral
said that economic and foreign policies pursued by the Deve Gowda
government would be maintained and further strengthened. On the
foreign policy initiatives taken by the previous government,
specially in the context of improving relations with neighbors
including Pakistan, he said that all foreign policy initiatives
would continue.
</P>
<P>
Congress President Sitaram Kesri, who took part in the
swearing-in ceremony here today, said that the new UF government
under the leadership of I. K. Gujral would remain safe and stable.
The Congress would always extend cooperation to the UF and it
would not destabilize the government. On March 30, Kesri suddenly
announced that his party withdrew its support to the Gowda
government, which was voted out in Parliament on the late evening
of April 11.
</P>
<P>
Trade and industry chambers of India today said that the
installation of the government headed by Prime Minister I. K.
Gujral would ensure stability and provide a stimulus to economic
decision-making. Welcoming Gujral's commitment to the UF's common
minimum program, the apex trade organizations hoped that the
government would speed up implementation of various programs to
get the economy, hurt by political uncertainties, back on track.
</P>
<P>
Required by the president, the new prime minister will seek a
vote of confidence in the Lok Sabha (Lower House of Parliament)
Tuesday and he is expected to obtain a majority in the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
