<HEADLINE> S. African Govt Vows to Improve Police Morale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- South African Police
Commissioner George Fivaz admitted that domestic police had
morale problems, but denied it as popular in the police service.
</P>
<P>
Local daily the Citizen today quoted Fivaz as saying that
police officials are uncertain about their country, their duties
and the police.
</P>
<P>
However, he insisted that "a large number of police officials
are still very positive."
</P>
<P>
Fivaz made the remarks in Pretoria, the administrative capital
of South Africa, after a memorial service for the 211 police
officials who died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by police authorities, 69 percent of
respondents in the police said they had no confidence in the
police management while 35 percent even indicated that they were
considering leaving the police.
</P>
<P>
Fivaz said it was normal for the morale graph to go downward
when South Africa is in a process of transformation.
</P>
<P>
"We estimated that it would take between five and eight years
before the situation would improve and it is very probable that
we will see a dramatic improvement from the next year on ward,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of this year 54 police died with 20
being on duty at the time of their death.
</P>
<P>
Up to March this year, a total of 39 police officials also
have committed suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
