<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Inspects Flood-Hit Lindi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa on Sunday pledged governmental actions to ease the
food shortage facing Lindi region and other areas hit by floods
and other natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
He appealed for local efforts to plant fast-maturing crops to
complement relief supplies in Mandawa in Kilwa District after
inspecting flood-hit Kilwa District and helicopter-affected Lindi
District.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said he had come to Mandawa to convey his personal
condolences to the area where 46 people were killed by the
floods last month.
</P>
<P>
A total of 61 people died on Lindi region, 58 of them
from Kilwa District.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa paid tribute to Lindi regional leaders, religious,
non-governmental and international groups and donor countries for
their offer of food, clothing and medicine to some 170,000 people
in eight villages of Kilwa and Lindi districts.
</P>
<P>
He contributed one million Tanzania Shillings (about 1,600
U.S. Dollars) to support the work of a youth group including the
building of permanent houses for the homeless in Mandawa
division.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to move away from flood-prone lowlands and
resettle on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, accompanied by Ngombale-Mwiru, returned to Dar es
Salaam Sunday night. 
</P>
