<HEADLINE> Manila Sends Investment-promoting Mission to Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has sent a
high-level trade mission to European countries in a bid to attract
more foreign investments in major infrastructure projects under
its build-operate-transfer (BOT) program.
</P>
<P>
The mission, headed by Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar
Bautista, is set to hold talks with investors in Paris, Dusseldorl
and London in an effort to entice them to invest in the country's
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
The mission, which also includes 10 other high-ranking
officials and 15 corporate executives, gets the coordination
assistance from former Foreign Affairs Secretary Roberto Romulo
and Henry Schumacker of the European Chamber of Commerce in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
BOT is a scheme developed by the country with assistance from
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines attracted a total investment of 28.7 billion
U.S dollars from both foreign and local investors last year, a
growth of 23 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This year, the country is considering sending
investment-promoting missions to major investing countries as a
major way to help attract foreign investments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
