<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A commentary by Xinhua News
Agency today repudiates the Dalai Lama's remarks over the past
several decades, which have disrupted stability and development in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The article "An Apologist for Peace or A Fomenter of Riots"
reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
For a long time the Dalai Lama has run about overseas preaching
his doctrine repeatedly, giving lengthy speeches and interviews
with foreign media, speaking glibly about his alleged goal of
"turning the Tibetan Plateau into a holy land filled with peace
and non-violence, where people can live in harmony with nature",
and that "only when the whole Earth is regarded as one family and
are our family members, will mankind be able to continue to
survive."
</P>
<P>
He has also claimed that what he has done "is entirely for the
happiness of the Tibetan people," and has masqueraded himself as
an apologist for peace and "Ahimsa" (Love and Non-violence).
</P>
<P>
However, there is an old Tibetan saying that goes, "mere talk
only churns up bubbles, but doing practical things is digging
gold", so, behind all this talk about "Ahimsa", what has the Dalai
Lama really done? History and fact provide us with the answer.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama has stayed outside China for 38 years, since
fleeing overseas after the failed armed rebellion of March, 1959
in Lhasa by a small number of splittists of the Tibetan
upper-class. Since then, he has gone farther and farther down the
road of dividing the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In the 1960s, he and his followers set up overseas the "Exiled
Tibetan Government", whose "head of state" was he himself. He
re-organized the rebellious forces and harassed the Chinese border
militarily for a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
These activities were aided by intelligence services of a
certain Western power, which taught the splittists "guerrilla
tactics" at its military bases and sent them into Tibet for the
purpose of sabotage and murder. These facts came to light in an
article in the "Chicago Tribune" on January 20. It said that:
</P>
<P>
-- In the 1970s, the Dalai Lama's clique began overseas radio
broadcasts in the Tibetan language to Tibet to create and spread a
great number of rumors. The act was intended to produce political
chaos, instigate separation, and incite contradictions among
ethnic groups, and preach confrontation in Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- From 1979 to 1980, China's Central Government agreed that
the Dalai Lama could send people to visit Tibet. The "visiting
group", however, took advantage of the opportunity to fan the
flames of "Tibetan independence" in Lhasa and other places. A
"visiting group" headed by Zhaidong Danzim Namgyai started giving
demagogic speeches in front of the Johkang Temple as soon as they
got off the bus. They then organized an illegal gathering at the
Gandain Monastery to overtly push for "Tibetan independence".
</P>
<P>
-- In 1986, the Dalai Lama's clique frequently held
"high-level" meetings in Dharmsala, India, where they tried to
mobilize people and plan riots in Lhasa. These included the sixth
meeting of the "Tibetan Youth Federation"; the first working
conference of the "Association of Tibetan Women"; a seminar on
"Tibetan Independence Campaign"; and a special political education
meeting for officials above grade nine, the themes of all of which
were "taking concrete actions for the independence of Tibet".
</P>
<P>
-- In April 1987, the Dalai Lama's clique held various meetings
in Dharmsala again, where they drew up action plans for a series
of riots and splitist activities, organizing illegal
demonstrations and creating social chaos in Tibet. Then, the
"Tibetan Youth Federation" sent people surreptitiously into Lhasa
and other places in Tibet from time to time to stir up unrest,
joining forces inside Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- On September 21, 1987, the Dalai Lama addressed the US
Congress, and on the 24th held a press conference at the
University of Indiana, where he openly claimed that "Tibet is not
a part of China and is an independent state". After these
addresses were broadcast to Tibet by the Dalai Lama's radio
station outside China and through other channels, serious rioting
broke out in Lhasa on the 27th. Shouting "Tibetan Independence",
rioters attacked local government buildings, damaged automobiles,
looted, started fires in shops and public buildings, and injured
many on-duty police officers.
</P>
<P>
A series of ensuing riots in Lhasa resulted in deaths and
further injuries and serious property losses, greatly affecting
normal life of local residents and a normal production order. They
paralyzed the Moinlam Qenmo, Tibetan Buddhism's most solemn
religious ceremony, which was to take place January 3-15.
</P>
<P>
In March 1988, rioters attacked the office in charge of summon
ceremony under the Lhasa Buddhist Association, killing a Tibetan
squad leader of the armed police, injuring 399 people, and
looted hotels and restaurants in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
In March the next year, Lhasa was hit by riots again. Within
two days rioters killed many innocent people, wounded more than
100 others, looted and destroyed more than 900 shops, attacked 24
government offices, enterprises and schools, and destroyed and
burned some 20 automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama delivered a speech encouraging this after each
riot and called on splittists to continue their activities. On
October 7, 1987, he made a speech in Dharasala, expressing his
"full support" to the riots in Lhasa. On the fifth day after the
rioting, which broke out in Lhasa on March 5, 1988, he lavishly
praised the riot in Lhasa at a gathering where he said, "Tibetans
inside China have high morale and great determination, and dare to
shed blood and make sacrifices."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The democratic reforms in Tibet in 1959 put an end once and for
all to the barbarous and backward serfdom during the Dalai Lama's
rule combining political and religious power and brought about
tremendous changes in the destiny and lives of the Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy for Tibetans has increased substantially from
36, before 1959, to today's 65. The Tibetan population, which had
remained around one million for several hundred years, has more than
doubled over the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
In the past, there were only a few schools in Tibet, which
accommodated monks and the children of aristocrats. Illiterates
and semi-literates accounted for more than 90 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 3,000 schools at various levels in
Tibet, and 73.5 percent of Tibetan children of school age have had
access to an education.
</P>
<P>
In old Tibet, there were only two small government-run clinics
in Lhasa. But the region now has over 1,000 medical institutions,
with 2.3 hospital beds and 2.1 doctors for every 1,000 people, a
larger figure than for the rest of the country on average.
</P>
<P>
A road network of more than 20,000 kilometers has been built in
Tibet that previously did not have a single road and relied
entirely on humans and animals for transport.
</P>
<P>
Electricity was not available in Tibet formerly, but there are
now more than 500 hydro-electric power stations, with a combined
annual output of over 300 million kilowatt-hours, and a number of
such stations are being built.
</P>
<P>
In the past, there were nearly 1,000 families of beggars and
poor people in areas around Lhasa, which was a city of only
20,000, living in huts made from broken gunnysacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was also common to see everywhere in Lhasa "prisoners" in
handcuffs, shackles, and wooden cangues begging along the
streets. These scenes are long gone in Tibet, and the overwhelming
majority of farmers and herdsmen in the autonomous region now have
enough food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that Tibet has scored great development and
progress and is making further progress. It is the common
aspiration of the Tibetan people and it is in their fundamental
interests that their standard of living continues to improve with
social and economic development. But it is only in an environment
of social stability that this can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
What has the Dalai Lama in fact done during these years? He
has done nothing for social and economic development in the region
or for improvement of people's living standard.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, he has given no thought to the fundamental
interests of the country and the Tibetan people, and, in order to
achieve his political aims of "Tibetan independence", he has made
up lies, created animosity between different ethnic groups, and
has tried everything possible to stir up riots in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He hopes that this will impede the development and progress of
the region and will help separate Tibet from the motherland and
restore his rule. How dare he call this "bringing happiness to the
Tibetan people"?
</P>
<P>
Former serfs and slaves in Tibet, who now have become masters
of their own destiny, will never allow themselves to return to the
dark and miserable past. The Dalai Lama's political conspiracy to
stir up social riots in Tibet is doomed to a complete failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama: Promoter of Peace Or Fomenter of Riots? (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The facts show that the Dalai Lama is not the "apologist of
peace" as he pretends to be, but is the fomenter of repeated chaos
in Tibet under the banner of "Independence of Tibet".
</P>
<P>
He professes to be the "protector of the snowland" and claims
that his actions are all for the welfare of the Tibetan
people. But, the facts tell a different story.
</P>
<P>
In old Tibet, under the Dalai Lama's rule, more than 95 percent
of the population were serfs or slaves, who were subject to cruel
oppression and exploitation by the three manorial lords.
</P>
<P>
Alexandra David-Neel, the famous French explorer and
Tibetologist who visited Tibet three times, and Sir Charles Bell,
a senior British officer who held posts in Tibet and Sikkim for 21
years, and who claimed to be a close friend of the earlier Dalai
Lama, made detailed descriptions of the cruel oppression the serfs
and slaves suffered and of their tragic life in their books; in
the case of the former, "Le Vieux Tibet Face A La Chine Nouvelle",
and the latter, "Tibet: Past and Present".
</P>
<P>
"...the exorbitant taxes and levies and heavy corvee imposed on
them...They were never paid any salary, nor were they given any
food.
</P>
<P>
"All these farmers were pitiable serfs, and they had no right
to leave their native place, which was impossible anyway, for
another land with a headman who was less harsh. Some of them had
fled to neighboring areas, only to be abducted by their former
headmen from their new homes, and brought back to their native
villages to be clubbed and fined a huge sum of money.
</P>
<P>
"For fear of the punishments the headman would inflict on their
families, those who wanted to flee did not dare to leave. If one
fled, one's families could be in hot water."
</P>
<P>
"Tibet was still in the feudal age, with its aristocracy
holding absolute power and haing vast influence. The nobility
could exercise official power upon the tenant-peasants...They
could at any time inflict punishments on the peasants, which
ranged from confiscation of draught animals, fining, caning,
short-term custody, to all other kinds."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
