<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac will announce this evening the
dissolution of the National Assembly (lower house of parliament) and
the organization of early legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the first secretary of the opposition Socialist Party,
Lionel Jospin, announced last evening the platform for his party's
legislative campaign, which rejects the rigid criteria set by the
Maastricht Treaty for entering the European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
-- Citing ``insufficient evidence,'' Israeli judicial authorities
saved on Sunday Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu from judicial
prosecution, while Netanyahu himself accused his political opponents
of conspiring a plot against him by creating a political scandal.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Fifty-three percent of the French people think that a
dissolution of the National Assembly will be a good thing, while 33
percent consider it a bad thing, and 14 fail to give their opinion,
according to a opinion poll conducted by Le Figaro and the SOFRES
polling institute.
</P>
<P>
The poll also shows that the ruling Rassemblement pour la
Republique and Union pour la Democratie Francaise will lose 150
seats in early legislative elections, but they will maintain
parliamentary majority with about 318 seats, 40 seats more than an
absolute majority required. 
</P>
