<HEADLINE> 26 Rebels Killed in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-six rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA) were killed on Saturday in northern Uganda
in its attack on Uganda's government troops, the New Vision
reported today.
</P>
<P>
LRA launched an attack on Acet Encampment of the Ugandan army
in Kitgum District at 5:00 a.m. local time, Colonel Katumba
Wamala, acting commander of the fourth division of the army.
</P>
<P>
Uganda army lost three soldiers in the battle, he added.
</P>
<P>
LRA rebels also launched several skirmishes in Gulu District
on Saturday. Three people were killed by land mines planted by the
LRA rebels.
</P>
<P>
There are two LRA groups now active in the northern districts
of Gulu and Kitgum.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ugandan army invited journalists to visit its camp in
Ngomoromo where 114 Sudanese soldiers and LRA rebels it captured
reportedly in a border clash south of the Uganda-Sudan border on
April 14 were paraded on April 19.
</P>
<P>
Wamala said that the seized Sudanese soldiers and the LRA
rebels entered Uganda together on April 14 from Juba, southern
Sudan, to set up a new camp to avoid the attack of Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
However, Sudanese Captain Abdalla Eltayib in Juba has denied
his unit cooperated with LRA members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
