<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Attack Government Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) guerrillas have launched separate attacks against
Philippine government troops over the weekend despite scheduled
peace talks this week.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported today that two government
soldiers were hurt Sunday morning in an attack staged by the MILF
near Carmen town in the southern province of Cotabato.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Captain Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the
Army's Sixth Infantry Division, as saying that the wounded were
members of a military unit tasked to guard a nearby irrigation
project.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were on their way back to the headquarters when
they were attacked by a number of MILF rebels, Detoyato said. He
said he did not know if the enemy side suffered casualties in the
20-minute firefight.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, MILF rebels have also been repeatedly harassing
military installation of government troops for the past three days
in Buldon town in Maguindanao province, where 10 students and a
teacher were killed in an attack last month.
</P>
<P>
The intermittent attacks started last Friday, but Detoyato
said, there are no government casualties reported during the
series of MILF offensives.
</P>
<P>
"We just responded with enough firepower to prevent them from
closing in (our) position," he said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, government troops Sunday overran a
military base of the MILF in Zamboanga del Norte, killing four
commanders and several MILF fighters and bringing the total number
of MILF deaths to 25 in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato said that such attacks by the MILF should be prevented
by their leaders so as not to jeopardize the ongoing peace talks
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Government and MILF peace negotiators are set to resume their
third round of talks on April 23 in an attempt to possibly forge a
general ceasefire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-member MILF is a break-away faction of the
mainstream Moro National Liberation Front which signed a final
peace agreement with the government last September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Extends Food Aid to Refugees in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program announced
today a one-year extension of its refugee feeding operation in
Kenya which will cover a planned caseload of 158,000 refugees,
mainly Somali and Sudanese.
</P>
<P>
In a WFP press release reaching here today, the orgnization's
latest extension of food assistance, which will start July 1,
1977, is valued at about 17.8 million U.S. Dollars including
food, transport, monitoring and distribution costs.
</P>
<P>
"Since WFP started feeding more than 400,000 refugees in 1991,
over half of them have gone home," said Mike Sackett, WFP's
country director for Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"But thousands remain in the northern and northeastern parts
of the country, and they will need our assistance until they feel
secure enough to return to their countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Somali refugee are located in camps in
the Dadaab area, in the district of Garissa in North Eastern
Province. The main camp housing the Sudanese refugees in in
Kakuma, Turkana District. Forty-nine percent of the refugees
are women.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1991, WFP has supplied a total of
318,945 tons of food commodities for the refugees in Kenya at an
estimated cost of 182 million U.S. Dollars, said the WFP report.
</P>
<P>
But WFP needs 30,000 tons of wheatflour, vegetable oil,
pulses, sugar, blended food and iodized salt food for the
latest expansion of the refugee operation, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Invites Malaysian Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Hungary is inviting
Malaysian businessmen to invest in a wide range of areas which
could be tapped under various privatization programs.
</P>
<P>
Areas that can be tapped by Malaysian investors include those
in infrastructure development, transport, power plant equipment
and sub-stations, General Director of the Hungarian Ministry for
Industry, Trade and Tourism Judit Fekete Gyarfas said here today.
</P>
<P>
Privatization is the main engine of Hungary's transformation
from a planned economy to a free market economy over the past
seven years, she said at a press conference on the eve of the
"Hungarian Business Opportunities -- Exhibition, Seminar, Business
Talks" to be held here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 16 companies will participate in the event which also aims
to promote trade between the two countries, the official who is
accompanying Prime Minister Gyula Horn on a two-day official visit
to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Gyarfas said Hungary, a small central European country, has
attracted more than 15 billion U.S. dollars in foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
On Hungarian investments in Malaysia, she said the amount is
still very small and there is room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
A Hungarian company, Ganz-Hunslet, was awarded a contract to
refurbish 40 bogies for Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia-Hungary bilateral trade totaled 62.8 million U.S.
dollars in 1996, up 76 percent from 46.5 million U.S. dollars in
1995, in Malaysia's favor, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's exports to Malaysia were mainly steel products,
pharmaceuticals, rolling stock parts, electronic parts, machine
tools and other machinery.
</P>
<P>
Its imports from Malaysia included computers and other
electronic products, palm oil, rubber, agricultural products,
textiles, shoes and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Hungary and Malaysia signed here today an agreement on
scientific and technological cooperation and a memorandum of
understanding on trade promotion cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Horn, who arrived here earlier today, had talks with his
Malaysian counterpart Mahathir Mohamad, and both witnessed the
signing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Advance Party Enters Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A 40-strong advance party of
the People Liberation Army (PLA) arrived at the Prince of Wales
Barracks in Central Hong Kong at 2:35 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
The PLA contingent, comprising 22 field officers, eight junior
officers and nine soldiers, entered Hong Kong by road through Lok
Ma Chau Crossing at 1:05 p.m. today. In full uniform, the PLA men
drove in by eight cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
At the Prince of Wales Barracks, Major General Bryan Dutton,
commander of the British Garrison, greeted Major General Zhou
Borong, deputy commander of the future PLA Hong Kong Garrison, who
led the advance personnel into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news briefing shortly after arrival, Zhou said:
"We come to Hong Kong just 71 days away from July 1, 1997. I and
my officers will make full use of the valuable time. We expect
support and cooperation from the British side and hope the two
sides can make joint efforts for the smooth transfer of defense
responsibility for Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that in accordance with the agreement reached at
the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG), the main task of the
PLA advance party is to make all necessary preparations for the
PLA to take over responsibility for defense of Hong Kong on July
1, 1997. "This (the arrangement) is of great significance to
enhance mutual understanding and cooperation between the Chinese
and British armed forces," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a simple welcoming ceremony, Major General Bryan
Dutton said: "This is a historic moment for both British and
Chinese armed forces. We will be working hard together to achieve
our common purpose -- the smooth transfer of defense for Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
The commander of the British forces promised to "give the
future garrison every possible assistance as they prepare for
their role".
</P>
<P>
The PLA advance unit will be divided into two, with 28 placed
at the Prince of Wales Barracks and 12 in military accommodation
on Stonecutter Island, the future navy base for the PLA. Their
work in the next ten weeks will include familiarization with the
14 military sites to be taken over, liaison with the British
Garrison and Hong Kong government and coordination of
communications support.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
