<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Identify Landslide Prone Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Ministry of Housing,
Construction and Public Utilities has launched a program to
identify landslide prone areas, according to the ministry sources
here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that steps would be taken to carry out
necessary safeguards under this program to minimize disasters in
the future.
</P>
<P>
They noted that landslides were one of the worst disasters
which affects Sri Lanka resulting in deaths.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the sources said that the ministry has drawn up a
project which could help map out landslide-prone locations.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Minister N. S. De Silva as saying: "The
government has taken steps to create a public awareness campaign
to guide them as to how they should go about taking preventive
measures and the need for vigilance. This program is the first of
its kind."
</P>
<P>
Under the mapping project, an area of 1,200 sq. km has already
been mapped out and 30 maps have been completed, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources are confident that these maps will help identify
the landslide locations to both the public and private sectors in
their plans for development activities in the hill areas of the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
