<HEADLINE> Zambian Ruling Party Demands Relocation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's ruling party has
demanded the relocation of the headquarters of the opposition
United National Independence Party (UNIP), claiming that its
current location is a threat to public peace.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka District Youth Chairman Michael Bwalya of the ruling
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) demanded on Sunday a immediate
removal of the UNIP headquarters from capital LUSAKA to a place
where its internal conflicts will not affect the public.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail reported today that two UNIP factions, one
supporting Sam Moyo, an expelled member of the UNIP central
committee, and another one loyal to UNIP leader Kenneth Kaunda,
clashed on Saturday at the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Bwalya said the headquarters has become a fighting scene of
UNIP which affected innocent people, discouraged investment and
disrupted local residents' daily life.
</P>
<P>
He refuted claims that his party was behind Moyo's protest
march.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moyo, who was expelled earlier this month for
"conducts which as compromised the standing of the party", has
refuted charges that he has been bought by MMD, insisting he is
still a UNIP member.
</P>
<P>
Lungu said the confrontation was organized by Lusaka Province
MMD Chairman Christopher Chawinga, adding he was allegedly seen
at the scene of the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
