<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Resumption of Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman of Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat denied in Gaza
Sunday night press reports that the PNA has resumed security
cooperation with Israel, the state-run Israel Radio reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeineh, Arafat's spokesman, emphasized that such
cooperation will not be resumed until Israel holds the expansion
of Jewish settlements in the West Bank and puts an end to the
construction of a new Jewish settlement at Har Homa in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Television and Army Radio reported over the weekend
that Arafat had agreed to a resumption of the cooperation,
stalled for the past month, after he met with Israeli Chief of the
General Staff Lt.-Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak and U.S. Middle East
peace coordinator Dennis Ross Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat's another spokesman, Marwan Kanafani, said in
Gaza that the problem the Palestinians are having with the
Israelis is not security cooperation, but that Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu should make up his mind to get back
on the right track of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction to Israel's Attorney-General Eliyakim
Rubinstein's decision not to indict Netanyahu in the Bar-On
corruption scandal, Kanafani said that since Netanyahu is cleared
now of the charges, he should make a serious consideration on
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been on the full alert throughout
the country fearing that terrorist attacks should occur during
the Jewish Passover holiday which lasts from April 21 to 28 this
year. A total indefinite closure imposed on the West Bank
Tuesday night remains in force. The closure does not include the
Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
