<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Russia Seek Investment Opportunities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of French and Russian
firms seeking new investment opportunities in east Africa has
increased with many selecting Kenya as the base for their
regional operations.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, three new French companies -- Sanofi,
Baccmus and AGS -- have set up offices in Kenya while Renault,
which was absent for a long time, is back to the Kenya's tire
market.
</P>
<P>
According to the French Trade Commission in Nairobi, more
French companies are seeking information on investment
opportunities in Kenya than ever before.
</P>
<P>
Pascal Maccioni, Trade Commissioner of the French Embassy to
Kenya, was quoted as saying here recently that "we see
Sub-Saharan Africa as the last frontier for French investment."
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that France was facing increasing competition in
Francophone countries and French companies had to take a wider
view of the global market.
</P>
<P>
Internal conflicts in some Francophone countries such as
Rwanda, Burundi and Zaire has discouraged French firms for
further investment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Local industrial sources said that French firms would have to
compete with the companies of Britain, the United States,
Germany, Japan, Korea and India.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia is also making its efforts to expand export
operations in the east African region with two trade delegations
touring Kenya recently.
</P>
<P>
A cultural and trade delegation of 200 private businessmen,
tourists and media personnel just ended a week-long visit to
Nairobi and Mombasa on April 18.
</P>
<P>
A delegation organized by Russian manufacturers from Moscow
is scheduled to visit Kenya from April 27 to seek investment
partners and plan a meeting with regional manufacturers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Using More Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing municipality has approved
172 overseas-funded firms in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The city used 830 million US dollars in overseas funds during
the period, 589 million of which was direct investment, according
to the local foreign trade and economic cooperation commission. The
commission says that more multinationals have invested in the city.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 14 new overseas-funded projects invested
ten million US dollars each. Of the world's 500 largest companies,
136 have offices in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to the city's development plan, priority in overseas
investment is being given to urban infrastructure, technological
upgrading, tourism, and housing.
</P>
<P>
During the January-March period, 51 percent of overseas funds
went to the service sector, up from last year's 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 12,000 overseas-funded
firms in Beijing, with a total overseas investment of 19.89
billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
