<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Gujral, Veteran Freedom Fighter, Politician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- I. K. Gujral, who was sworn in
as India's 12th prime minister here today, is a veteran freedom
fighter and statesman in the country enjoying high prestige.
</P>
<P>
He was born on December 4, 1919 at Jhelum town (now in
Pakistan). Inspired by his parents, who actively took part in
India's struggle against British colonialism and for independence,
he joined the national movement at the age of 11. He began his
political life when he was a student in Lahore's colleges serving
as president of Lahore students' union and general secretary of
the Pubjab unit of All India Students' Federation.
</P>
<P>
Partition of the Indian Subcontinent in 1947 brought the Gujral
family to Delhi and I.K. Gujral devoted himself to the
rehabilitation of thousands of people displaced by the partition.
His stint with big-time politics began when he joined the Congress
Party in the 1950s and became the vice-president of New Delhi
Municipal Committee in 1959, a post he held till 1964.
</P>
<P>
He was elected to Rajya Sabha (Upper House of Parliament) from
Delhi on a Congress ticket in 1964 and three years later he made
his debut as an administrator when he was appointed minister of
state for parliamentary affairs. Re-elected to Rajya Sabha in
1970, he remained its member till 1976 and held several portfolios
in the Indira Gandhi government before he was sent as India's
ambassador to the Soviet Union. He later parted ways with the
Congress and was actively associated with the move for opposition
unity in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, he entered the Lok Sabha (Lower House of Parliament)
and served as external affairs minister in the V.P. Singh
government, which lasted just less than one year. He again became
external affairs minister in the Deve Gowda government when it
came to power on June 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Gujral has launched a series of initiatives to improve India's
relations with its neighbors. As a result, India and Bangladesh
signed a historic Ganges water-sharing treaty in December last
year, removing a major long-standing irritant in their bilateral
relations. Last month, he, in a bid to boost ties with Pakistan,
announced measures to ease travel restrictions on Pakistani
nationals, an action that contributed to the resumption of
Indo-Pak foreign secretary level talks stalled for over three
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
