<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Ensures Smooth Food Supplies to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The No. 753 train, which starts
from Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang Province, has
delivered more than 2.6 million tons of cargo to Hong Kong in the
past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the three speediest freight trains whose sole
purpose is to provide livestock and fresh and frozen food to Hong
Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
The trains went into operation in 1962 on orders of late
Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou Railway Sub-Bureau has given priority to the
loading and operation of the No. 753 train, to ensure the
sufficient, safe and quick transport of goods to Hong Kong,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that Jinhua, a major pig-raising base in
China, delivered a total of 463 cars of pigs to Hong Kong last
year, compared with less than 70 cars in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the past five years show that 96.8 percent of the
trains arrived in Hong Kong on schedule, with the rate topping the
list of all cargo trains in the country.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all the pigs and cattle on Hong Kong's market are
supplied by the three fast trains, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
