<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Third Wave of Immigrants (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Fast economic growth in
Shanghai, especially in the Pudong New Area, has resulted in the
city's "third wave" of immigrants in 150 years.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say a great number of professionals from China
and overseas continue to flow here at the rate of 100 per day.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey shows that each month the municipality has an
average of ten new businesses started by Chinese students who have
returned from abroad, and the total number has come to 400 now.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest city of immigrants, Shanghai's prosperity
has long been tied to talent coming from outside since it became
an opening trading port more than 150 years ago. The first peak
occurred in the 1930s. Shortly after that Shanghai grew into the
biggest trade, finance and manufacturing center in China and the
Far East.
</P>
<P>
The second peak came in the 1950s when New China was founded
and the city grew into China's biggest industrial base and
all-purpose central city.
</P>
<P>
Sun Changmin, director of the Population and Development
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences Shanghai
Branch said, "The third wave of talent now will far exceed the
previous two waves in scale and the impact on Shanghai's social
and economic development."
</P>
<P>
More than 17,000 students studying overseas have come to work
in Shanghai. Some have started manufacturing businesses in the
three parks specially designed for them, others working in hi-tech
research programs.
</P>
<P>
Dr. He Lin, of the Shanghai Life Science Research Center of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, is one example of those students who
have returned from overseas. He now heads a research team
researching genes that may lead to diseases like Alzheimer's
Disease and to cures. He left the Edinburgh Human Genetics
Institute of the British Academy of Medical Sciences in 1996,
where he had worked for many years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Third Wave of Immigrants (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A recent survey showed that 70 to 80 percent of Shanghai's
young people are satisfied with the city's political and economic
situation and cultural atmosphere, and 86 percent believe that
Shanghai has the most development opportunities for anyone.
</P>
<P>
There has obviously been a cooling down of the craze to go
abroad in the late 1980s and early 1990s. Statistics of the
Municipal Public Security Bureau show that more than 40,000 people
here applied to go abroad for language study in 1988 alone,
compared with 600 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of people from Hong Kong, Macao, or Taiwan who have
worked or lived in the city for more than a year is greater than
33,000. There are also more than 10,000 foreign experts and
scholars working on key projects, or in major scientific research,
educational programs, or other areas.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has grown into an international metropolis of
concerts, first-class museums, and libraries, with a myriad of
commercial opportunities available.
</P>
<P>
There are about 16,000 overseas-backed enterprises
here. Industrial output value of overseas-funded enterprises rose
35 percent in 1996 from the previous year, and sales increased 47
percent.
</P>
<P>
There are 38 foreign banks authorized to do business in the
city, which reported an increase of 42 percent in annual profits.
</P>
<P>
In addition to having recruited annually 10,000 college
graduates and more than 3,000 people with senior technological and
management titles, Shanghai has issued blue cards for long-term
residence to over 2,500 people from other parts of China, who have
invested 4.74 billion yuan, including 286 million U.S. dollars in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Huang Dalin, a native of Wenzhou City, in east China's Zhejiang
Province, who has gotten his blue card, said, "I found that
Shanghai had the most development potential after travelling
extensively over the past decade." He added that he plans to move
his company headquarters from Qinhuangdao City in Hebei Province
to Shanghai, after having invested 10 million yuan in it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
