<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commercial Swindles Harm Chinese Consumers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide survey has shown
that 78.4 percent of Chinese consumers have been affected by
commercial swindles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The annual survey, conducted by the China Consumers'
Association, places so-called "direct sales" at the top of its
list of commercial swindles, today's China Business Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Direct sales mean manufacturers selling directly to consumers
to reduce prices by chopping off profit margin reaped by the
distributor. But in fact, in many of these "direct sales",
consumers are duped into buying goods that are priced higher than
normal or that are fake.
</P>
<P>
Direct sales ranked No. 9 in 1995's survey of bad business
practices, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the number of complaints lodged by consumers was up
almost 50 percent from 1995, which shows that more and more people
are aware of the importance of protecting their own economic
rights, according to the association. Consumers said they were
most unhappy about the following: repair work, food service,
medical care, public utilities, clothes, washing and dyeing,
entertainment, house purchases, and interior decoration.
</P>
<P>
To protect consumers' rights, the paper says, the government
will increase its efforts to crack down on commercial
swindles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0181 </DOCNO>
