<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: PLA Forces to Be Stationed in HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Forty advance personnel of the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) arrived in Hong Kong today to make
practical preparations for the PLA garrison's stationing in the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the first batch of the advance personnel of the
PLA marks the progress of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group
(JLG) in their 12-month talks concerning the entry of the advance
contingent in HK.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the military forces of the PLA to be stationed
in the HKSAR was completed on January 28, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Made up of PLA ground, naval and air forces and with strict
political, military, and disciplinary training, the forces will be
officially stationed in Hong Kong at zero hour on July 1.
</P>
<P>
All members in the forces were selected strictly. They have
been required to study the Basic Law and Hong Kong's local laws,
customs, economy, geography, as well as the English language.
</P>
<P>
The military forces have been formed in accordance with the PLA
missions stipulated in the Constitution of the People's Republic
of China, and the relevant stipulation of the Basic Law that the
Central People's Government shall be responsible for the defense
of the HKSAR, in a bid to safeguard the state sovereignty,
reunification and territorial integrity and maintain the
prosperity and stability of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The military forces will not interfere in local affairs of the
HKSAR.
In addition to abiding by the national laws, members of the
garrison shall abide by the laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure of the garrison shall be borne by the Central
People's Government.
</P>
<P>
The military forces have received Hong Kong people from various
sectors, including the news media.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with mainland and Hong Kong journalists, Major
General Liu Zhenwu, commander of the forces, said that his forces
and the HKSAR government will operate separately according to
their respective military and executive systems and will not
interfere in each other's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Liu paid two working visits to Hong Kong last July and August
at the invitation of Commander of the British Garrison Major
General Bryan Dutton and with the arrangement of the JLG.
</P>
<P>
On December 30, 1996, the 23rd Session of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) endorsed
the Law on Stationing Troops in the HKSAR which received positive
response from people of various sectors in HK.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the law fully represented the Chinese
government's stance that the PLA forces are necessary for
safeguarding state security and maintaining HK's stability and
prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
