<HEADLINE> China To Set Up First Agro-science Pilot Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN. April 21 (Xinhua) -- China will build its first
agricultural high-tech pilot zone in Yangling, northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, as part of the efforts to feed its increasing
population and narrow the gap between east and west.
</P>
<P>
The zone will cover 20 sq km, consisting of a science park,
several experimental bases, and the new area to build necessary
facilities on, said Jia Zhibang, deputy governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
The program aims at developing applied science and research,
and putting high-tech research achievements in production and
market. China's vast northwest has great potential for
contributing to the country's grain production.
</P>
<P>
Yangling, a district of Xianyang city, is said to be the cradle
of China's agriculture, and has long been known as China's largest
agro-science city, in which are located 10 universities and
research institutes of agriculture, forestry, and water
conservancy, as well as five large-scale agricultural laboratories
and more than 270 regular labs, with over 4,100 staff and workers,
including some famous agronomists.
</P>
<P>
The area lies in between where northern climate joins with the
southern climate, and has diversified farm production conditions.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 projects involving 13 industries in the zone have
been listed for domestic and overseas investment, Jia
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
