<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake-hit Lijiang Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua)-- The 800-year-old town of Dayan in
earthquake-hit Lijiang County of South China's Yunnan Province is
making strenuous efforts to reclaim its former glory, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
M A Halim, a UN-designated expert on historic relics is making
a three-day tour of Lijiang to decide whether to place the town on
the UN World Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
"It is rare for a county to apply for world heritage after an
earthquake," said Chen Jiang, deputy-magistrate of Lijiang Naxi
Minority Autonomous County.
</P>
<P>
Dayan makes up 80 percent of the county shattered by an
earthquake measuring 7 on the Richter scale in February last year,
with economic losses climbing to 4.6 billion yuan (554 million Us
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The UN granted Lijiang 30,000 US dollars to encourage it to
overcome its difficulties.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars) has been
allocated by the government for reconstruction. "Over 20 million
yuan (2.4 million US dollars) has been spent to make the town look
like what it was," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Starting in June, an even more ambitious rebuilding project
should begin with the assistance of an expected World Bank loan.
</P>
<P>
The project to be completed by August next years, aims to
rebuild the house of the Mu Clan, the "forbidden city" of the
town, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"A world-famous and prosperous Lijiang will greatly benefit the
local people," said Zhang Yunping, another deputy-magistrate of
the county.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
