<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Declines in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's external trade
continued to decline in March as total trade in the month
decreased by 2.3 percent on a three-month moving basis, the
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports declined by 4.1 percent, re-exports
fell by 0.6 percent, while oil domestic exports dropped by 4.3
percent in March, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, non-oil domestic exports decreased by 2.1
percent in March this year, the TDB said, commenting that although
this was less severe than the 7.9 percent contraction in the
previous month, it reflected continued weakness in the global
demand for some electronics and related products such as
semi-conductors.
</P>
<P>
As a result of its 4.1 percent decline, non-oil domestic
exports shrank to 7.7 billion Singapore dollars (about 5.35
billion US dollars) in March. The TDB said that the performance of
key markets remained mixed.
</P>
<P>
While non-oil domestic exports to the United States, Japan and
Hong Kong were still weak, non-oil domestic exports to the
European Union and Malaysia went up by 4.9 percent and 2.7 percent
respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that oil domestic exports decreased by 4.3 percent in
March with the softening of oil prices as well as a drop in volume
due to lackluster demand from Japan and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
According to the TDB figures, imports fell by 1.9 percent to
16.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 11.67 billion US dollars) in
March. Decreases were reflected in imports of integrated circuits,
parts of diodes, photocells and transistors, capacitors, and other
products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
