<HEADLINE> Middle Schools Say "No" to Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Two middle schools in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region have called on students
to say no to cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The No. 26 Middle School of Nanning, in the autonomous regional
capital, and Jiangnan No. 1 Middle School in Chongzuo County have
been named test sites for a China-Unicef smoking prevention
program in the country's autonomous areas inhabited by ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six schools in China are now involved in the program,
jointly sponsored by the Unicef and the Chinese Government. The
program is scheduled to run from 1996 to around the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey of 70 middle schools in China last year,
22 percent of the students in township junior middle schools have
smoked at least one cigarette; in urban junior middle schools,
19.7 percent; and 36.7 percent in urban senior middle schools.
</P>
<P>
The two schools in Guangxi will promote an anti-smoking drive
among the students and encourage schools, parents and communities
to ban smoking for middle school students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
