<HEADLINE> Bhutanese Refugees in Nepal Condemn Leader's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 Bhutanese refugees
Sunday staged a demonstration in an eastern Nepali town in protest
of the arrest of a refugee leader by Indian authorities, reports
reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees from eight refugee camps in east Nepal also held a
mass meeting in Damak, about 250 km from here, to call for
immediate release of Rongthong Dorij, who was arrested in a New
Delhi suburb Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of Dorij, chairman of refugee political group the
United Front for Democracy (UFD), was illegal as a Bhutanese
national can freely travel in India without passport under an
existing treaty between Bhutan and India, refugees said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian authorities reportedly charged the Bhutanese refugee
leader for violating the Foreigners' Registration Act.
</P>
<P>
According to UFD sources, Dorij had gone to India to mobilize
support for his organization's program against the Bhutanese
authorities, which have forced some 100,000 refugees to flee to
Nepal since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, various Nepali social organizations Sunday also
flayed Dorij's arrest in India and have planned to organize
protest programs including sit-in in front of the Indian Embassy
here to press for his release, the local press said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
