<HEADLINE> Thailand to Hold Festival to Promote Beef Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Several Thai government agencies
are joining hands to organize a festival to promote beef
consumption as fears of anthrax are haunting the country.
</P>
<P>
The event is being organized by the interior, agriculture and
public health ministries in Nonthaburi province at a time when
beef sales are falling around the country among fears of anthrax,
a disease which could be transmitted from cattle to humans.
</P>
<P>
The Public Health Ministry said that it will issue certificates
to slaughter houses and sellers, while helping training them to
ensure that the beef sold will be free of anthrax.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry has imposed strict measures on imports
of cows and buffaloes in border provinces to ensure that all
cattle imported are vaccinated before being sold in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Local beef sellers claimed that their daily sales dropped
nearly 90 percent following the reports on the outbreak of anthrax
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Thai public health officials said that the disease is
non-communicable to human beings and it can be destroyed under 140
degrees Celsius temperature for one to three hours or if exposed
under 100 degrees Celsius of moist heat for five to 30 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
