<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools to Protect Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China will establish a number of
green schools to help protect environment in the country by the
turn of the century, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted information from the National
Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA) as saying that students in
these schools will have access to materials concerning
environmental protection distributed by the environmental
departments. They will also be required to master the
environmental protection contents in their textbooks.
</P>
<P>
But the sources did not elaborate how many green schools will
be set up this year.
</P>
<P>
Green Schools must improve not only their own teachers' and
students' environmental awareness but also that of neighboring
units, and must keep their school yards clean and beautiful,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Education materials satisfying different needs of colleges,
professional, high and primary schools for environmental education
will be edited and published in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
This program initiated by NEPA is designed to guide the
environmental education and publication work throughout the
country. Its goal is to help the country's young people and
children obtain basic knowledge of environmental conservation by
the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and members of the Chinese Communist
Party, as well as enterprises' legal persons, should receive some
training on environmental conservation and sustained development,
according to the program.
</P>
<P>
All on-job officials in education and environmental departments
should also receive comprehensive training on environment-friendly
economic development.
</P>
<P>
By the year of 2010, the environmental education system will be
standardized and regulated in accordance with regulations, as
targeted by the program.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 160 universities and college across China
training majors of the environment. Many institutions of
higher learning are offering optional courses on environmental
protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
