<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Successfully Enforces Forest Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province in southeast
China has been successful in implementing the country's Forest
Law, with its afforestation rate ranking highest in China.
</P>
<P>
A just-ended 12-day inspection tour of the province's forests,
led by Vice-Chairman Buhe of the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress, the country's top legislature, found
Fujian has worked steadily to enforce the law since it went into
effect on January 1, 1985.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the top legislature has organized such
an inspection. Other tour teams were sent to Jiangxi and Yunnan
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Fujian included in its overall Forestry Law enforcement plan
legal education for the public on forestry, local regulations on
protection of forests, crackdowns by local protection teams and an
improved supervisory system.
</P>
<P>
But the inspection group also found that there is still much to
be done in terms of forestry tax collection, over-cutting of woods
and forest mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
To date, Fujian's afforestation rate has reached 57.3 percent,
ranking first in the country, and forestry has become its pillar
industry.
</P>
<P>
China's afforestation rate is 13.92 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
