<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Televised Network Takes Medicare to Patients' Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A televised network will enable
Chinese patients living in remote areas to share the country's
best medical counselling and diagnosis service without leaving
their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide communication network will provide long-distance
counselling and treatment on illness for patients throughout China
as it goes into operation next month, according to a report in
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Several types of personal health cards are to be launched
through banks in May, which record detailed health data of card
holders and serve as a reference for the accurate and quick
diagnosis and treatment of health problems, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The card, a laser information carrier with the same size as a
credit card, can save character and image information and can also
be used to settle payments.
</P>
<P>
Apart from long-distance medical counselling and diagnosis
given by the country's best doctors, the network will hold
nationwide television conferences and carry out professional
training and international exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
The network, called "Golden Health Medical Network", will
initially cover 20 hospitals in 15 cities in May, and expand to 80
medical units by the end of this year. By the end of the year
2000, it will include a total of 500.
</P>
<P>
The final goal is to link up with all hospitals above the
county level as well as some of the township hospitals, the report
quoted Liu Yinghua, who is working with the Ministry of Health to
establish the network, as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are currently more than 60,000 hospitals in the country,
while 80 percent of highly skilled doctors and specialized medical
equipment are concentrated in hospitals in large cities.
</P>
<P>
Quite a number of the rural population do not have access to
immediate treatment for their illnesses, especially many difficult
cases.
</P>
<P>
Many of them travel to big city hospitals to have their
illnesses diagnosed and cured, which is however time-consuming and
expensive, often requiring additional expenses for transportation
and accommodations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hangzhou Adds More Green To West Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Hangzhou, capital of east
China's Zhejiang Province, is carrying out a plan to add more
green around the West Lake, a famous tourist spot.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the city, more tall buildings are being
built around the lake. To protect the landscape of the whole lake
area, the city has decided to plant flora around these buildings.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 various kinds of vegetation have been planted
around the buildings in the vicinity of the lake for the past two
years. Contracts have been signed between garden departments and
residential quarters or working units to cultivate more green
plants around those tall buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
