<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Volume to Reach 310-Billion-Dollar goal in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua)-- A senior Chinese trade official is
urging calmness, despite the prediction that China will achieve
this year's targeted 310 billion US dollars in foreign trade
volume, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics indicate that during the first quarter this
year, China's foreign trade stood at 64.29 billion US dollars, up
11.6 percent from a year ago, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 25.7 percent to 35.5 billion US dollars, creating
a trade surplus of 6.71 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter's growth in exports was based upon the
figures of the same period in 1996 when China's foreign trade
suffered a downturn," said Liu Shanzai, vice-minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the first quarter's export volume only accounts for
a small share of the year's total.
</P>
<P>
Difficulties such as money-strains on State foreign trade firms
still exist.
</P>
<P>
"It is still an arduous task to fulfil the year's 155 billion
US dollars export target," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He called on domestic manufacturers to attach special
importance to improving economic efficiency while trying to sign
more export contracts at the 81st Chinese Export Commodities
Fair which runs through April 30.
</P>
<P>
The deals concluded in the first four days indicate that China
has enough goods to sell abroad as a result of the country's sound
economics performance, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
An export-oriented economy has become a "dragon head" of the
country's economy, but State-owned firms of foreign trade need to
shake off heavy burdens and gear themselves to the market economy,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Establishing joint projects should be another good
opportunity." Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that more than 270,000 overseas firms have
invested in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
