<HEADLINE> Gansu's Nonferrous Metal Industry Flourishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 21 (Xinhua)-- Northwest China's Gansu Province
is expected to accelerate the building of five nonferrous metal
production bases along the ancient "Silk Road".
</P>
<P>
The province is rich in nonferrous metals. The reserves of
nickel, cobalt, platinum, palladium, and iridium rank first in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Gansu has invested 11.37 billion yuan to build a complete
system for nonferrous metal production covering prospecting,
exploiting, dressing, smelting, and processing. Currently, it is
capable of smelting 591,000 tons of nonferrous metals a year.
</P>
<P>
The province has the country's largest rare earth production
base at Jingyuan, an aluminum-smelting base at Lanzhou, and a
nickel and cobalt production base at Jinchuan.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Province has exported a dozen kinds of nonferrous metals
including nickel, cobalt, and rare earth to Japan, France,
Germany, the Unites States, and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Gansu has risen from the last but two place to the fourth place
in the nation in terms of production scale of nonferrous metals,
which has become its pillar industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
