<HEADLINE> WTO Team Formed to Settle Thai-U.S. Shrimp Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and the United States
have agreed on the members of a team formed by the World Trade
Organization (WTO) to settle their dispute over shrimp trade.
</P>
<P>
The team consisting of three experts respectively from Britain,
Germany and Brazil was appointed early this month to review a U.S.
ban on shrimp imports from Thailand, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed a ban on shrimp imports from Thailand last
year, claiming Thailand could not provide sufficient protection on
sea turtles. But it lifted the ban in November, saying that it was
satisfied with the improvement made by Thailand through installing
turtle excluder devices on trawlers.
</P>
<P>
Despite the U.S. lifting of the ban, Thailand insisted in
filing a complaint with the WTO, saying it wanted a clear
explanation from the U.S. behind the motive.
</P>
<P>
Krirk-krai, Thailand ambassador to the WTO, said recently that
according to the agreements under the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade (GATT), member states could not ban imports of products
by applying non-tariff measures.
</P>
<P>
Import bans are allowed only for reasons based on the quality
of the products, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ban had nothing to do with product quality, he added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
