<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (35-36) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (35-36)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What are principal officials in the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Apart from the Chief Executive, principal officials in
the government of Hong Kong SAR include the Secretaries and Deputy
Secretaries of Departments, Directors of Buries, Commissioner
Against Corruption, Director of Audit, Commissioner of Police,
Director of Immigration and Commissioner of Customs and
Excise. Such posts can only be held by Chinese citizens among
permanent residents of the region with no right of abode in any
foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Question: Why should Hong Kong's political system continue to
be executive-led after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: One of the most striking features of the executive-led
political system is that executive organs perform primary
governmental functions, with the legislature playing the role of
supervision and power balancing. Many factors have contributed to
the success of Hong Kong, and the executive-led political system
is one of the most important.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is not a country but an international economic
metropolis. This requires that the local government makes prompt
decisions and executes them promptly. And this calls for an
executive-led political system. If it wants to continue its status
as one of the world's economic centres after 1997, Hong Kong
should continue to have an executive-led political system. That is
why the future Hong Kong political system as stipulated in the
Basic Law is of an executive-led type. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
