<HEADLINE> Manila Mulling Import Tax to Protect Local Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Board of
Investments is finalizing a proposal to impose tax on a wide range
of imported products to help local industries cope with trade
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times reported today that the proposal was outlined
in a 1997 memorandum prepared for the board's governing body by
executive director Elmer Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the proposed tax will be slapped on
four general categories including electronics, chemicals,
automotive and machinery parts and components.
</P>
<P>
The memo did not mention specific products that would be
affected, but sources from the Board of Investments said the
products probably include tires, television sets, stereo
components, video projectors and video cassette players.
</P>
<P>
Local makers of these products have been vigorously lobbying
for government protection against competing foreign brands, the
board's proposal is an offshoot of these lobbying efforts, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
However, the proposed import tax is expected to come under fire
from the Philippines' trading partners because it violates the
World Trade Organization's rules prohibiting member countries from
imposing a discriminatory tax on imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
