<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Support Ban of Vicious Dogs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Most New Zealanders favor
banning pit bull terriers, a kind of vicious dogs which have
caused a number of incidents of serious attack of people in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 750 people conducted recently shows that only 19
percent opposes a ban, while 75 percent of those polled favor
banning the dog, the local paper The Dominion reported today.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party MP Jim Sutton, who issued the survey results
Sunday, said action should be taken before these "dangerous
animals" cause any more injuries or death.
</P>
<P>
The call for a ban of the dog came after a man in Te Puke on
North Island was mauled to death earlier this month by a dog
reported to have pit bull bloodlines. The tragedy sparked off a
debate in New Zealand whether this kind of dangerous dog should be
allowed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, New Zealand's first Pet Exposition held in the South
Island city of Christchurch at the weekend banned pit bulls.
</P>
</TEXT>
