<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, China Take Two More Golds Apiece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GOTHENBURG, Sweden, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Australia and China
took two more gold medals apiece on the final day of the world
short-course swimming championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Dunn took the men's 200 meters individual medley gold
while Grant Hackett won the men's 1,500 meters freestyle.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Dunn repeated the individual medley golden
double he achieved at the last edition of the championships in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Dunn also won a relay gold and was named men's swimmer of the
championships. American Jenny Thompson of the United States
earned the women's award for her haul of two golds and two
silvers.
</P>
<P>
China also won two gold medals through its women's 4X100
meters medley relay quartet and Chen Yan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese quartet narrowly missed their third relay world
record but still managed to edge the American team for the gold.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan beat Misty Hyman of the United States to win the
women's 200 meters backstroke. The fancied American got only two
silver and three bronze medals in the championships.
</P>
<P>
China got six gold medals through its female swimmers, only
behind overall leader Australia.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Sanchez of Venezuela and Cuba's Neisser Bent both
completed golden doubles while Louise Karlsson won Sweden their
third gold in the championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
