<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broad Prospects for Sino-Russian Economic, Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- People in Moscow often go to the
hundreds of shopping stalls owned by Chinese in the Izmailovo
market to buy good-quality clothing, toys and electrical
appliances at low prices.
</P>
<P>
In Russia's border cities, China-made commodities are
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
And in China's border cities, commodities imported from Russia,
such as machinery, electrical equipment, metals and fertilizers,
are shipped to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Frequent commercial exchanges and several scheduled flights a
week between the two countries... all suggest a prosperous future
for Sino-Russian economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade relations between the two countries have
developed quickly in recent years, with the bilateral trade
turnover hitting a record high of 7.68 billion U.S. dollars in
1993.
</P>
<P>
Despite a slip in bilateral trade in 1994 as a result of
changes in their respective demands, the two sides managed to
bring the turnover to 5.46 billion dollars in 1995, and 6.85
billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Russia has now become the eighth largest trading partner of
China, and China, Russia's third largest trading partner,
excluding Russia's trading partners within the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
In a recent survey by the Russian International Sociological
Research Center, 52 percent of respondents said Russia should give
priority to developing economic and trade ties with China.
</P>
<P>
And 87 percent of the entrepreneurs in the survey regarded
China as a potential partner for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries' economies and bilateral trade strongly
complement each other," Economic and Commercial Minister-Counselor
Geng Xuncai, of the Chinese Embassy in Russia, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
China's exports to Russia are mainly food, daily necessities,
and light industrial and textile products. The major imports from
Russia are power equipment, transport machinery, metals and
chemical products, according to Geng.
</P>
<P>
He said China had build several thermal power stations by using
Russia-made complete kits of equipment, which had greatly
contributed to the power supply in China.
</P>
<P>
However, several problems remain to be solved. One was China's
big deficit in trade. Last year, China had a trade deficit of 3.5
billion dollars with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese counselor pointed out that China and Russia had
much potential in expanding economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
For example, the two sides could raise the trade volume by
developing trade in technology, expanding the scope of economic
and technological cooperation, and improving the structure of
their exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two sides could also increase their
investment in each other and cooperate in "trans-century"
projects. Russia invested 22 million U.S. dollars in China in
1995, while China utilizes 30-40 billion dollars in foreign
capital each year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, China invested 40 million dollars in Russia
in 1995, while Russia attracts several billion dollars in foreign
investment a year.
</P>
<P>
The two could cooperate in projects such as laying the
Irkutsk-China-South Korea gas pipelines, in the construction of
China's Three-Gorges Project, and in laying oil pipelines and
erecting electricity transmission lines from Russia's East and
West Siberias to Northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The two sides could also set up a China trade center in Moscow,
and open shops there for Chinese commodities to show quality
products produced in China to the Russian people, the Chinese
counselor said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries could achieve the target of
raising bilateral trade to 20 billion dollars by the year 2000, a
strategic objective proposed by leaders of China and Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Wins Men's 4x100 Meters Freestyle Relay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GOTHENBURG, Sweden, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany edged host
Sweden in an exciting race to win the men's 4X100 meters freestyle
relay at the world short-course swimming championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The race marked the competitive farewell of Anders Holmertz of
Sweden, who had won two Olympic silvers and a bronze in individual
freestyle races.
</P>
<P>
Holmertz swam the second leg and took over in fourth place. He
moved the Swedish team to the third place with a split of 48.84
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Australia led the first two legs of the race through
Michael Klim and Scott Logan. But Alexander Luederitz pushed
Germany ahead on the third leg.
</P>
<P>
Lars Frolunder overhauled Australia's Jeffrey English in the
final leg but he could not catch Germany's Aimo Heilmann.
</P>
<P>
Germany won the race in 3 minutes 14.08 seconds, followed by
Sweden in the second place at 3:14.22. Australia finished third
at 3:14.83. 
</P>
</TEXT>
