<DOCNO> XIE19970421.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB: Asia's Megacity Problems Avertible With Proper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Asia's megacities -- areas with a
population over 10 million -- will expand from nine to 20 by the
year 2025, but megacity problems, such as rise in congestion,
pollution and crimes, can be averted with proper management, the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) said today.
</P>
<P>
"The continuing migration from rural to urban areas in Asia
will expand the number of megacities from nine to 20 by the year
2025," the bank said in its "Annual Report 1996," which was
released here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, over the past 30 years, Asia's urban
population has nearly tripled from 400 million to 1.1 billion and
there has been a corresponding increase in the level of
urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Today, Asia has nine megacities -- Beijing, Bombay, Calcutta,
Jakarta, Osaka, Seoul, Shanghai, Tianjin and Tokyo, but soon four
more will be added -- Bangkok, Dhaka, Karachi and Manila, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said that while the megacities are often
plagued by environmental deterioration, inadequate housing,
traffic jams and social alienation, they are also important to a
country's economic development and can provide residents with a
satisfying quality of life.
</P>
<P>
"Asia's megacities can also offer efficient business conditions
and a better standard of services than in rural areas," it said.
</P>
<P>
Though the megacities have negative features, the chilling
prospect of a serious deterioration in quality of life could be
averted, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the gaps between demand and supply in Asia's
megacities are management related.
</P>
<P>
The bank suggested that the government should shift its role as
a service provider to a facilitator of services provided by
others.
</P>
<P>
It also called for moves toward decentralization and
strengthening of local government and the provision of services
such as water supply and public transportation through
public-private partnership.
</P>
<P>
The bank estimated that to provide services at levels
sufficient to sustain productivity in megacities, 20 billion to 40
billion U.S. dollars will be needed annually over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Transport and communications, energy and water supply and
sanitation will form the largest capital investment segments, the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
But it is difficult to predict what will happen if there are
shortfalls in the financing of megacity growth and management, the
bank added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
